on 'er own to enjoy it.

239
00:20:29,320 --> 00:20:31,610
If that ain't worth 'alf a crown
now and again...

240
00:20:31,690 --> 00:20:33,850
...l'll take my belt off and give 'er what for.

241
00:20:33,950 --> 00:20:37,150
You got a good 'eart.
But you want a 'alf a crown out o' Eliza...

242
00:20:37,240 --> 00:20:38,950
...you better have a good story.

243
00:20:39,040 --> 00:20:40,780
Leave that to me, my boy.

244
00:20:41,540 --> 00:20:44,540
-Good mornin', George.
-Not a brass farthin'.

245
00:20:51,720 --> 00:20:53,540
Not a brass farthin'.

246
00:22:14,810 --> 00:22:16,010
There she is.

247
00:22:24,530 --> 00:22:26,820
Why, Liza, what a surprise.

248
00:22:27,780 --> 00:22:30,730
Hop along, Charlie, you're too old for me.

249
00:22:31,160 --> 00:22:34,080
-Don't you know your daughter?
-You don't know what she looks like.

250
00:22:34,160 --> 00:22:37,000
I know 'er, I know 'er.
Come on, I'll find 'er.

251
00:23:06,410 --> 00:23:07,950
Eliza, what a surprise.

252
00:23:08,030 --> 00:23:09,610
Not a brass farthin'.

253
00:23:09,780 --> 00:23:11,990
Hey, you come 'ere, Eliza.

254
00:23:12,200 --> 00:23:14,450
I ain't gonna take me 'ard-earned wages...

255
00:23:14,540 --> 00:23:17,410
...and let you pass 'em on
to a bloody pubkeeper.

256
00:23:24,720 --> 00:23:27,750
You wouldn't send me 'ome
to your stepmother...

257
00:23:27,850 --> 00:23:30,850
...without a drop o' liquid protection,
would ya?

258
00:23:30,930 --> 00:23:32,930
Stepmother, indeed!

259
00:23:33,140 --> 00:23:36,260
Well, I'm willin' to marry 'er.
It's me that suffers by it.

260
00:23:36,360 --> 00:23:38,430
I'm a slave to that woman, Eliza.

261
00:23:38,520 --> 00:23:41,480
Just because I ain't 'er lawful 'usband.

262
00:23:41,690 --> 00:23:42,730
Come on.

263
00:23:42,820 --> 00:23:45,860
Slip your ol' dad just 'alf a crown
to go 'ome on.

264
00:23:46,200 --> 00:23:48,870
Well, I had a bit o' luck meself last night.

265
00:23:52,710 --> 00:23:56,210
But don't keep comin' around
countin' on 'alf crowns from me!

266
00:23:56,500 --> 00:23:59,500
Thank you, Eliza. You're a noble daughter.

267
00:24:02,380 --> 00:24:06,220
'"Beer, beer, glorious beer

268
00:24:06,850 --> 00:24:08,510
'"Fill yourself right up'"

269
00:24:28,870 --> 00:24:31,330
See this creature
with her curbstone English...

270
00:24:31,420 --> 00:24:35,500
...that will keep her
in the gutter till the end of her days?

271
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:39,790
In six months, I could pass her off
as a duchess at an Embassy Ball.

272
00:24:40,130 --> 00:24:43,090
I could get her ajob as a lady's maid
or a shop assistant...

273
00:24:43,180 --> 00:24:45,340
...which requires better English.

274
00:24:53,520 --> 00:24:57,020
You disgrace to the noble architecture
of these columns!

275
00:25:03,240 --> 00:25:06,160
I could get her ajob as a lady's maid
or a shop assistant...

276
00:25:06,250 --> 00:25:08,400
...which requires better English.

277
00:25:34,940 --> 00:25:37,070
How many vowel sounds
did you hear altogether?

278
00:25:37,150 --> 00:25:38,860
I believe I counted 24.

279
00:25:38,990 --> 00:25:42,070
Wrong by 100. To be exact you heard 130.

280
00:25:42,660 --> 00:25:44,290
Listen to them one at a time.

281
00:25:44,370 --> 00:25:47,370
Must l? I'm really quite done up
for one morning.

282
00:26:11,570 --> 00:26:13,030
Your name, please?

283
00:26:13,690 --> 00:26:15,020
Your name, miss?

284
00:26:15,110 --> 00:26:18,030
My name is of no concern to you
whatsoever.

285
00:26:18,160 --> 00:26:19,950
One moment, please.

286
00:26:28,960 --> 00:26:31,580
London is gettin' so dirty these days.

287
00:26:32,170 --> 00:26:35,380
I'm Mrs. Pearce, the housekeeper.
Can I help you?

288
00:26:35,640 --> 00:26:39,250
Good morning, missus.
I'd like to see the professor, please.

289
00:26:39,390 --> 00:26:40,970
Could you tell me what it's about?

290
00:26:41,060 --> 00:26:43,850
It's business of a personal nature.

291
00:26:45,900 --> 00:26:47,390
One moment, please.

292
00:26:56,990 --> 00:26:59,660
-Mr. Higgins?
-What is it, Mrs. Pearce?

293
00:26:59,750 --> 00:27:02,280
There's a young woman
who wants to see you, sir.

294
00:27:02,370 --> 00:27:03,570
A young woman?

295
00:27:04,750 --> 00:27:05,750
What does she want?

296
00:27:05,840 --> 00:27:08,590
She's quite a common girl, sir.
Very common indeed.

297
00:27:08,670 --> 00:27:10,710
I should've sent her away, only I thought...

298
00:27:10,800 --> 00:27:12,790
...you wanted her to talk
into your machine.

299
00:27:12,880 --> 00:27:15,670
-Has she an interesting accent?
-Simply ghastly.

300
00:27:15,760 --> 00:27:18,760
Good. Let's have her in.
Show her in, Mrs. Pearce.

301
00:27:19,560 --> 00:27:23,010
This is rather a bit of luck.
I'll show you how I make records.

302
00:27:23,100 --> 00:27:27,020
We'll set her talking, then I'll take
her down first in Bell's Visible Speech...

303
00:27:27,110 --> 00:27:30,280
...then in broad Romic.
Then we'll get her on the phonograph...

304
00:27:30,360 --> 00:27:34,780
...so you can turn her on when you want
with the written transcript before you.

305
00:27:38,040 --> 00:27:39,830
This is the young woman, sir.

306
00:27:39,910 --> 00:27:41,190
Good mornin', my good man.

307
00:27:41,290 --> 00:27:43,200
Might I 'ave a word with you?

308
00:27:43,290 --> 00:27:45,780
Oh, no. This is the girl
I jotted down last night.

309
00:27:45,880 --> 00:27:49,130
She's no use. I got the records I want
of the Lisson Grove lingo.

310
00:27:49,220 --> 00:27:51,130
I won't waste another cylinder on that.

311
00:27:51,220 --> 00:27:52,840
Be off with you. I don't want you.

312
00:27:52,930 --> 00:27:56,100
Don't be so saucy.
You ain't 'eard what I come for yet.

313
00:27:56,270 --> 00:27:58,060
Did you tell 'im I come in a taxi?

314
00:27:58,140 --> 00:28:01,180
Nonsense. Do you think a gentleman
like Mr. Higgins cares...

315
00:28:01,270 --> 00:28:02,430
...what you came in?

316
00:28:02,520 --> 00:28:04,100
Oh, we are proud.

317
00:28:04,270 --> 00:28:07,520
He ain't above givin' lessons, not 'im.
I 'eard 'im say so.

318
00:28:07,610 --> 00:28:09,690
I ain't come here to ask
for any compliment...

319
00:28:09,780 --> 00:28:12,530
...and if my money's not good enough,
I can go elsewhere.

320
00:28:12,620 --> 00:28:14,080
Good enough for what?

321
00:28:14,160 --> 00:28:15,900
Good enough for you.

322
00:28:17,040 --> 00:28:19,870
Now you know, don't ya?
I'm come to 'ave lessons.

323
00:28:19,960 --> 00:28:22,500
And to pay for 'em, too, make no mistake.

324
00:28:22,630 --> 00:28:23,620
Well!

325
00:28:24,420 --> 00:28:26,960
And what do you expect me to say?

326
00:28:27,760 --> 00:28:31,260
Well, if you was a gentleman,
you might ask me to sit down, I think.

327
00:28:31,350 --> 00:28:34,050
Don't I tell you I'm bringin' you business?

328
00:28:34,810 --> 00:28:36,760
Should we ask this baggage to sit down...

329
00:28:36,850 --> 00:28:39,260
...or shall we just throw her
out of the window?

330
00:28:39,350 --> 00:28:43,400
I won't be called a baggage.
Not when I've offered to pay like any lady.

331
00:28:44,610 --> 00:28:46,400
What do you want, my girl?

332
00:28:50,530 --> 00:28:52,360
I want to be a lady in a flow'r shop...

333
00:28:52,450 --> 00:28:55,290
...'stead of sellin' at the corner
of Tottenham Court Road.

334
00:28:55,370 --> 00:28:58,120
But they won't take me
unless I can talk more genteel.

335
00:28:58,210 --> 00:28:59,490
He said 'e could teach me.

336
00:28:59,580 --> 00:29:01,660
Well, 'ere I am ready to pay 'im.

337
00:29:01,750 --> 00:29:05,000
Not asking any favor
and he treats me as if I was dirt.

338
00:29:05,670 --> 00:29:09,540
I know what lessons cost as well as you do
and I'm ready to pay.

339
00:29:12,520 --> 00:29:13,840
How much?

340
00:29:14,310 --> 00:29:16,020
Now you're talkin'.

341
00:29:16,230 --> 00:29:18,770
I thought you'd come off it
for a chance to get back...

342
00:29:18,860 --> 00:29:20,980
...a bit of what you chucked
at me last night.

343
00:29:21,070 --> 00:29:22,770
You'd had a drop in, 'adn't you?

344
00:29:22,860 --> 00:29:24,060
Sit down.

345
00:29:24,200 --> 00:29:27,400
-If you're goin' t' make a compliment of it--
-Sit down!

346
00:29:28,370 --> 00:29:30,570
Sit down, girl. Do as you're told.

347
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:32,490
What's your name?

348
00:29:32,620 --> 00:29:34,530
Eliza Doolittle.

349
00:29:35,210 --> 00:29:37,660
Won't you sit down, Miss Doolittle?

350
00:29:41,550 --> 00:29:43,130
I don't mind if I do.

351
00:29:46,680 --> 00:29:49,800
How much do you propose
to pay me for these lessons?

352
00:29:50,020 --> 00:29:51,510
Oh, I know what's right.

353
00:29:51,600 --> 00:29:54,470
My lady friend gets French lessons
for 18 pence an hour...

354
00:29:54,560 --> 00:29:56,470
...from a real French gentleman.

355
00:29:56,560 --> 00:29:58,890
You wouldn't have the face
to ask me the same...

356
00:29:58,980 --> 00:30:01,820
...for teachin' me my own language
as you would for French.

357
00:30:01,900 --> 00:30:05,270
I won't give more than a shillin'.
Take it or leave it.

358
00:30:07,410 --> 00:30:10,490
Do you know, Pickering,
if you think of a shilling...

359
00:30:10,750 --> 00:30:14,830
...not as a simple shilling,
but as a percentage of this girl's income...

360
00:30:15,170 --> 00:30:17,870
...it works out as fully equivalent of...

361
00:30:19,590 --> 00:30:22,040
...60 or 70 pounds from a millionaire.

362
00:30:22,880 --> 00:30:26,300
By George, it's enormous.
It's the biggest offer I ever had.

363
00:30:26,390 --> 00:30:30,600
Sixty pounds? What are you talkin' about?
Where would I get 60 pounds?

364
00:30:30,680 --> 00:30:33,060
-I never offered you 60 pounds!
-Hold your tongue!

365
00:30:33,150 --> 00:30:34,770
But I ain't got 60 pounds!

366
00:30:34,860 --> 00:30:38,640
Don't cry, silly girl. Sit down.
Nobody's going to touch your money.

367
00:30:38,740 --> 00:30:42,070
Somebody'll touch you with a broomstick
if you don't stop sniveling.

368
00:30:42,160 --> 00:30:43,320
Sit down!

369
00:30:47,290 --> 00:30:49,820
Anybody'd think you was my father!

370
00:30:49,960 --> 00:30:53,570
If I decide to teach you,
I'll be worse than two fathers to you.

371
00:30:54,380 --> 00:30:55,370
Here.

372
00:30:55,670 --> 00:30:56,700
What's this for?

373
00:30:56,800 --> 00:31:00,580
To wipe your eyes. To wipe any part
of your face that feels moist.

374
00:31:00,800 --> 00:31:03,640
Remember, that's your handkerchief
and that's your sleeve.

375
00:31:03,720 --> 00:31:07,300
Don't confuse one with the other,
if you want to become a lady in a shop.

376
00:31:07,390 --> 00:31:11,220
It's no use to talk to her like that.
She doesn't understand you.

377
00:31:11,310 --> 00:31:14,930
Give the 'andkerchief to me.
He give it to me, not to you!

378
00:31:15,110 --> 00:31:17,100
Higgins, I'm interested.

379
00:31:17,280 --> 00:31:18,560
What about your boast...

380
00:31:18,650 --> 00:31:21,520
...you could pass her off as a duchess
at the Embassy Ball?

381
00:31:21,620 --> 00:31:24,450
I'll say you're the greatest teacher alive
if you do that.

382
00:31:24,540 --> 00:31:28,660
I'll bet you all the expenses
of the experiment that you can't do it.

383
00:31:28,870 --> 00:31:30,580
I'll even pay for the lessons.

384
00:31:30,670 --> 00:31:33,370
You're real good. Thank ye, Capt'n.

385
00:31:34,800 --> 00:31:36,750
It's almost irresistible.

386
00:31:39,470 --> 00:31:41,760
She's so deliciously low.

387
00:31:41,850 --> 00:31:43,390
So horribly dirty.

388
00:31:43,510 --> 00:31:47,050
I ain't dirty! I washed my face an' hands
before I come, I did.

389
00:31:47,140 --> 00:31:51,090
I'll take it. I'll make a duchess
of this draggle-tailed guttersnipe.

390
00:31:51,480 --> 00:31:55,020
We'll start today. This moment.
Take her away and clean her.

391
00:31:55,110 --> 00:31:58,530
Sandpaper, if it won't come off.
Is there a fire in the kitchen?

392
00:31:58,610 --> 00:32:01,650
Take her clothes off and burn them
and order some new ones.

393
00:32:01,740 --> 00:32:04,360
Just wrap her in brown paper
till they come.

394
00:32:04,870 --> 00:32:08,450
You're no gentleman, you're not,
to talk o' such things.

395
00:32:08,540 --> 00:32:10,040
I'm a good girl, I am.

396
00:32:10,130 --> 00:32:12,910
And I know what the likes of you are, I do.

397
00:32:13,590 --> 00:32:16,790
We want none of your slum prudery here,
young woman.

398
00:32:17,050 --> 00:32:19,290
You've got to learn to behave
like a duchess.

399
00:32:19,390 --> 00:32:22,840
Take her away, Mrs. Pearce.
If she gives you any trouble, wallop her.

400
00:32:22,930 --> 00:32:24,760
I'll call the police, I will.

401
00:32:24,850 --> 00:32:26,480
I've got no place to put her.

402
00:32:26,560 --> 00:32:28,520
Well, put her in the dustbin.

403
00:32:29,480 --> 00:32:31,470
Come, Higgins, be reasonable.

404
00:32:31,570 --> 00:32:34,140
You must be reasonable,
Mr. Higgins, you must.

405
00:32:34,240 --> 00:32:36,730
You can't walk over everybody like this.

406
00:32:39,490 --> 00:32:40,520
I?

407
00:32:41,330 --> 00:32:43,120
Walk over everybody?

408
00:32:43,200 --> 00:32:47,370
My dear Mrs. Pearce, my dear Pickering,
I had no intention of walking over anybody.

409
00:32:47,460 --> 00:32:50,630
I merely suggested we should be kind
to this poor girl.

410
00:32:50,750 --> 00:32:55,300
I didn't express myself clearly
because I didn't wish to hurt her delicacy...

411
00:32:55,720 --> 00:32:56,830
...or yours.

412
00:32:56,930 --> 00:33:00,010
But, sir, you can't take a girl up like that...

413
00:33:00,180 --> 00:33:02,800
...as if you were picking up
a pebble on the beach.

414
00:33:02,890 --> 00:33:04,060
Why not?

415
00:33:04,230 --> 00:33:07,020
Why not? But you don't know
anything about her.

416
00:33:07,110 --> 00:33:09,890
What about her parents?
She may be married.

417
00:33:10,110 --> 00:33:11,350
Garn!

418
00:33:11,690 --> 00:33:14,780
There. As the girl
very properly says, '"garn! '"

419
00:33:15,570 --> 00:33:17,230
Who'd marry me?

420
00:33:19,660 --> 00:33:21,450
By George, Eliza...

421
00:33:22,250 --> 00:33:25,660
...the streets will be strewn
with the bodies of men...

422
00:33:25,830 --> 00:33:29,420
...shooting themselves for your sake
before I'm done with you.

423
00:33:32,050 --> 00:33:33,210
I'm goin'.

424
00:33:33,510 --> 00:33:37,050
He's off his chump, he is.
I don't want no balmies teachin' me.

425
00:33:37,140 --> 00:33:40,310
Mad? All right, Mrs. Pearce,
don't order those new clothes.

426
00:33:40,390 --> 00:33:42,600
-Throw her out.
-Stop! I won't allow it.

427
00:33:42,690 --> 00:33:44,180
Go home to your parents, girl.

428
00:33:44,270 --> 00:33:46,020
I ain't got no parents.

429
00:33:46,230 --> 00:33:48,140
She ain't got no parents. What's the fuss?

430
00:33:48,230 --> 00:33:51,650
Nobody wants her. She's no use
to anyone but me. Take her upstairs!

431
00:33:51,740 --> 00:33:54,190
What's to become of her?
ls she to be paid anything?

432
00:33:54,280 --> 00:33:55,860
Do be sensible, sir.

433
00:33:56,160 --> 00:33:58,650
What'd she do with money?
She'll have food and clothes.

434
00:33:58,750 --> 00:34:00,320
She'll drink if you give her money.

435
00:34:00,410 --> 00:34:02,160
You are a brute! It's a lie!

436
00:34:02,250 --> 00:34:04,740
Nobody ever saw the sign o' liquor on me.

437
00:34:04,840 --> 00:34:07,920
Sir, you're a gentleman.
Don't let 'im speak to me like that!

438
00:34:08,010 --> 00:34:11,210
Does it occur to you, Higgins,
the girl has some feelings?

439
00:34:11,300 --> 00:34:14,420
No, I don't think so.
No feelings we need worry about.

440
00:34:14,640 --> 00:34:15,720
Well, have you, Eliza?

441
00:34:15,810 --> 00:34:18,130
I got me feelings same as anyone else.

442
00:34:18,230 --> 00:34:21,510
Mr. Higgins, I must know on what terms
the girl is to be here.

443
00:34:21,600 --> 00:34:24,010
What'll become of her
when you've finished teaching?

444
00:34:24,110 --> 00:34:25,930
You must look ahead a little, sir.

445
00:34:26,030 --> 00:34:29,280
What'll become of her if we leave her
in the gutter, Mrs. Pearce?

446
00:34:29,360 --> 00:34:31,690
That's her own business,
not yours, Mr. Higgins.

447
00:34:31,780 --> 00:34:33,320
When I'm done, we'll throw her back.

448
00:34:33,410 --> 00:34:36,740
Then it'll be her own business again.
That'll be all right, won't it?

449
00:34:36,830 --> 00:34:39,150
You've no feelin' 'eart in ya!

450
00:34:39,670 --> 00:34:42,160
You don't care for nothin' but yourself.

451
00:34:42,380 --> 00:34:44,580
I've 'ad enough of this. I'm goin'!

452
00:34:44,670 --> 00:34:46,710
You ought to be ashamed of yourself!

453
00:34:46,800 --> 00:34:48,710
Have some chocolates, Eliza.

454
00:34:55,470 --> 00:34:57,180
'Ow do I know what might be in 'em?

455
00:34:57,270 --> 00:35:00,390
I've 'eard of girls bein' drugged
by the likes o' you.

456
00:35:00,770 --> 00:35:02,350
Pledge of good faith.

457
00:35:03,020 --> 00:35:04,570
I'll take one half.

458
00:35:05,440 --> 00:35:07,150
And you take the other.

459
00:35:10,620 --> 00:35:13,700
You'll have boxes of them,
barrels of them every day.

460
00:35:14,080 --> 00:35:15,790
You'll live on them, eh?

461
00:35:17,250 --> 00:35:20,780
I wouldn't 've ate it, only I'm too ladylike
to take it out o' me mouth.

462
00:35:20,880 --> 00:35:24,380
Think of it, Eliza.
Think of chocolates, and taxis...

463
00:35:24,720 --> 00:35:27,090
...and gold and diamonds.

464
00:35:28,470 --> 00:35:32,220
I don't want no gold and no diamonds.
I'm a good girl, I am.

465
00:35:32,600 --> 00:35:35,880
Higgins, I really must interfere.
Mrs. Pearce is quite right.

466
00:35:35,980 --> 00:35:38,980
If this girl will put herself
in your hands for six months...

467
00:35:39,060 --> 00:35:43,610
...for an experiment in teaching, she must
understand thoroughly what she's doing.

468
00:35:47,740 --> 00:35:49,860
You are to stay here
for the next six months...

469
00:35:49,950 --> 00:35:53,950
...learning how to speak beautifully
like a lady in a florist shop.

470
00:35:55,170 --> 00:35:58,870
If you're good and do what you're told,
you'll sleep in a proper bedroom...

471
00:35:58,960 --> 00:36:03,260
...have lots to eat, money
to buy chocolates and take rides in taxis.

