What is wrong with that, young man?
I bet I got it right.

402
01:28:01,280 --> 01:28:02,350
Smashing.

403
01:28:02,650 --> 01:28:05,110
Has it suddenly turned chilly?

404
01:28:05,610 --> 01:28:08,980
I do hope we won't have
any unseasonable cold spells.

405
01:28:09,240 --> 01:28:11,230
They bring on so much influenza.

406
01:28:11,330 --> 01:28:14,080
And the whole of our family
is susceptible to it.

407
01:28:14,160 --> 01:28:18,490
My aunt died of influenza, so they said.

408
01:28:19,040 --> 01:28:22,830
But it's my belief they done
the old woman in.

409
01:28:24,050 --> 01:28:25,330
Done her in?

410
01:28:25,970 --> 01:28:27,670
Yes, Lord love you.

411
01:28:27,930 --> 01:28:30,170
Why should she die of influenza...

412
01:28:30,430 --> 01:28:34,210
...when she'd come through diphtheria
right enough the year before.

413
01:28:34,470 --> 01:28:36,680
Fairly blue with it she was.

414
01:28:37,350 --> 01:28:39,220
They all thought she was dead.

415
01:28:39,310 --> 01:28:43,440
But my father, he kept ladling gin
down her throat.

416
01:28:48,400 --> 01:28:52,780
Then she come to so sudden
she bit the bowl off the spoon.

417
01:28:54,070 --> 01:28:55,530
Dear me!

418
01:28:56,700 --> 01:29:00,040
Now what call would a woman
with that strength in her...

419
01:29:00,120 --> 01:29:02,030
...have to die of influenza?

420
01:29:02,750 --> 01:29:07,040
And what become of her new straw hat
that should have come to me?

421
01:29:09,630 --> 01:29:11,960
Somebody pinched it.

422
01:29:13,220 --> 01:29:15,010
And what I say is:

423
01:29:15,220 --> 01:29:18,170
Them 'as pinched it, done her in.

424
01:29:19,430 --> 01:29:21,970
Done her in? '"Done her in,'" did you say?

425
01:29:22,680 --> 01:29:24,340
Whatever does it mean?

426
01:29:24,480 --> 01:29:29,060
That's the new small talk.
'"To do somebody in'" means to kill them.

427
01:29:29,730 --> 01:29:32,820
But you surely don't believe
your aunt was killed?

428
01:29:33,400 --> 01:29:34,680
Do I not?

429
01:29:34,820 --> 01:29:39,810
Them she lived with would have killed her
for a hatpin, let alone a hat.

430
01:29:40,240 --> 01:29:42,650
But it can't have been right
for your father...

431
01:29:42,740 --> 01:29:45,580
...to pour spirits down her throat like that.

432
01:29:45,960 --> 01:29:47,620
It might have killed her.

433
01:29:47,710 --> 01:29:51,490
Not her. Gin was mother's milk to her.

434
01:29:51,880 --> 01:29:57,000
Besides, he poured so much down
his own throat he knew the good of it.

435
01:29:57,760 --> 01:29:59,500
Do you mean that he drank?

436
01:29:59,590 --> 01:30:02,430
Drank? My word. Something chronic.

437
01:30:06,270 --> 01:30:09,350
Here, what are you sniggering at?

438
01:30:10,020 --> 01:30:13,140
The new small talk.
You do it so awfully well.

439
01:30:13,360 --> 01:30:17,020
Well, if I was doing it proper,
what was you sniggering at?

440
01:30:17,990 --> 01:30:20,270
Have I said anything I oughtn't?

441
01:30:22,200 --> 01:30:23,780
Not at all, my dear.

442
01:30:23,990 --> 01:30:25,950
Well, that's a mercy anyhow.

443
01:30:28,950 --> 01:30:32,490
I don't know if there's time
before the next race to place a bet...

444
01:30:32,580 --> 01:30:34,410
...but come, my dear.

445
01:30:34,790 --> 01:30:38,460
I have a bet on number seven.
I should be so happy if you would take it.

446
01:30:38,550 --> 01:30:40,670
You'll enjoy the race ever so much more.

447
01:30:40,760 --> 01:30:42,380
That's very kind of you.

448
01:30:42,470 --> 01:30:43,580
His name is Dover.

449
01:30:43,680 --> 01:30:45,130
Come along.

450
01:30:48,600 --> 01:30:50,510
'"There they are again

451
01:30:50,600 --> 01:30:52,220
'"Lining up to run

452
01:30:52,680 --> 01:30:54,390
'"Now they're holding steady

453
01:30:54,480 --> 01:30:56,770
'"They are ready for it. Look!

454
01:30:57,810 --> 01:31:00,060
'"lt has begun'"

455
01:31:05,990 --> 01:31:07,780
Come on. Come on, Dover.

456
01:31:08,740 --> 01:31:09,740
Come on.

457
01:31:10,030 --> 01:31:11,660
Come on, Dover!

458
01:31:11,790 --> 01:31:12,820
Come on!

459
01:31:17,170 --> 01:31:21,330
Come on, Dover!
Move your bloomin' arse!

460
01:31:27,840 --> 01:31:29,220
Oh, my dear.

461
01:31:44,190 --> 01:31:48,060
You're not serious, Henry. You don't
expect to take her to the Embassy Ball.

462
01:31:48,150 --> 01:31:49,690
Don't you think she's ready for it?

463
01:31:49,780 --> 01:31:52,150
Dear Henry, she's ready for a canal barge.

464
01:31:52,240 --> 01:31:54,480
Her language may need
a little refining, but--

465
01:31:54,580 --> 01:31:58,190
Really, Henry, if you cannot see
how impossible this whole project is...

466
01:31:58,290 --> 01:31:59,950
...then you must be potty about her.

467
01:32:00,040 --> 01:32:02,110
I advise you to give up
and not put yourself...

468
01:32:02,210 --> 01:32:03,780
...or this poor girl through any more.

469
01:32:03,880 --> 01:32:06,410
It's the most fascinating venture
I've ever undertaken.

470
01:32:06,500 --> 01:32:09,950
Pickering and I are at it from morning
till night. It fills our whole lives.

471
01:32:10,050 --> 01:32:13,910
Teaching Eliza, talking to Eliza,
listening to Eliza, dressing Eliza.

472
01:32:15,090 --> 01:32:18,630
You're a pretty pair of babies
playing with your live doll.

473
01:32:18,720 --> 01:32:20,000
Here's the car.

474
01:33:41,220 --> 01:33:42,250
Good evening, sir.

475
01:33:42,340 --> 01:33:45,010
-Is dinner ready? I'm famished.
-Immediately, sir.

476
01:33:45,090 --> 01:33:47,170
Good evening, Professor Higgins.

477
01:34:04,780 --> 01:34:08,990
'"When she mentioned
how her aunt bit off the spoon

478
01:34:09,740 --> 01:34:13,030
'"She completely done me in

479
01:34:13,540 --> 01:34:16,910
'"And my heart went on
a journey to the moon

480
01:34:17,500 --> 01:34:22,130
'"When she told about her father
and the gin

481
01:34:22,800 --> 01:34:26,790
'"And I never saw a more enchanting farce

482
01:34:27,510 --> 01:34:32,470
'"Than the moment when she shouted
'Move your bloomin'--''"

483
01:34:33,180 --> 01:34:35,220
-Yes, sir?
-Is Miss Doolittle in?

484
01:34:35,310 --> 01:34:37,130
Whom shall I say is calling?

485
01:34:37,230 --> 01:34:40,510
Freddy Eynsford-Hill.
If she doesn't remember who I am...

486
01:34:40,650 --> 01:34:43,560
...tell her I'm the chap
who was '"sniggering'" at her.

487
01:34:43,650 --> 01:34:44,640
Yes, sir.

488
01:34:44,730 --> 01:34:46,640
And will you give her these?

489
01:34:47,110 --> 01:34:48,310
Wouldn't you like to come in?

490
01:34:48,400 --> 01:34:50,530
They're having dinner,
but you may wait in the hall.

491
01:34:50,610 --> 01:34:54,150
No, thank you. I want to drink in
the street where she lives.

492
01:35:02,500 --> 01:35:07,460
'"l have often walked
down this street before

493
01:35:08,300 --> 01:35:13,170
'"But the pavement always stayed
beneath my feet before

494
01:35:13,930 --> 01:35:18,880
'"All at once am I several stories high

495
01:35:19,560 --> 01:35:24,180
'"Knowing I'm on the street where you live

496
01:35:25,480 --> 01:35:30,440
'"Are there lilac trees in the heart of town?

497
01:35:31,150 --> 01:35:36,110
'"Can you hear a lark
in any other part of town?

498
01:35:37,030 --> 01:35:41,860
'"Does enchantment pour
out of every door?

499
01:35:42,660 --> 01:35:47,320
'"No, it's just on the street where you live

500
01:35:48,880 --> 01:35:53,370
'"And, oh, the towering feeling

501
01:35:54,210 --> 01:35:58,710
'"Just to know somehow you are near

502
01:36:00,470 --> 01:36:04,970
'"The overpowering feeling

503
01:36:05,520 --> 01:36:10,180
'"That any second you may suddenly appear

504
01:36:11,730 --> 01:36:16,520
'"People stop and stare,
they don't bother me

505
01:36:17,530 --> 01:36:22,190
'"For there's nowhere else on earth
that I would rather be

506
01:36:23,490 --> 01:36:26,490
'"Let the time go by

507
01:36:26,620 --> 01:36:30,620
'"l won't care if I

508
01:36:31,370 --> 01:36:36,030
'"Can be here on the street where you live'"

509
01:36:43,380 --> 01:36:45,290
I'm terribly sorry, sir.

510
01:36:45,430 --> 01:36:48,550
Miss Doolittle says she doesn't want
to see anyone ever again.

511
01:36:48,640 --> 01:36:50,350
But why? She was unbelievable.

512
01:36:50,430 --> 01:36:53,600
So I've been told, sir.
Is there any further message?

513
01:36:54,770 --> 01:36:56,010
Tell her that I'll wait.

514
01:36:56,100 --> 01:36:58,510
But it might be days, sir, even weeks.

515
01:36:58,610 --> 01:37:01,140
But don't you see? I'll be happier here.

516
01:37:10,080 --> 01:37:14,740
'"People stop and stare,
they don't bother me

517
01:37:16,080 --> 01:37:20,740
'"For there's nowhere else on earth
that I would rather be

518
01:37:21,920 --> 01:37:24,790
'"Let the time go by

519
01:37:25,470 --> 01:37:29,790
'"l won't care if I

520
01:37:30,760 --> 01:37:35,420
'"Can be here on the street where you live'"

521
01:37:45,610 --> 01:37:48,230
It really is, Higgins.
It's inhuman to continue.

522
01:37:48,320 --> 01:37:51,360
Do you realize what you've got to teach
this girl in six weeks?

523
01:37:51,450 --> 01:37:54,400
You've got to teach her to walk, talk,
address a duke, a lord...

524
01:37:54,490 --> 01:37:57,200
...a bishop, an ambassador.
It's absolutely impossible.

525
01:37:57,290 --> 01:38:00,820
Higgins, I'm trying to tell you
that I want to call off the bet.

526
01:38:00,910 --> 01:38:03,160
I know you're a stubborn man, but so am l.

527
01:38:03,250 --> 01:38:05,160
This experiment is over.

528
01:38:05,250 --> 01:38:09,580
And nothing short of an order
from the king could force me to recant.

529
01:38:11,590 --> 01:38:13,960
You understand, Higgins? It's over.

530
01:38:15,720 --> 01:38:18,510
Higgins, if there's any mishap
at the Embassy tonight...

531
01:38:18,600 --> 01:38:21,220
...if Miss Doolittle suffers
any embarrassment...

532
01:38:21,310 --> 01:38:22,550
...it'll be on your head alone.

533
01:38:22,640 --> 01:38:23,890
Eliza can do anything.

534
01:38:23,980 --> 01:38:25,770
Suppose she's discovered?
Remember Ascot.

535
01:38:25,850 --> 01:38:27,730
Suppose she makes
another ghastly mistake?

536
01:38:27,810 --> 01:38:30,480
There'll be no horses at the ball, Pickering.

537
01:38:32,530 --> 01:38:34,820
Think of how agonizing it would be.

538
01:38:34,900 --> 01:38:37,570
If anything happened tonight,
I don't know what I'd do.

539
01:38:37,660 --> 01:38:39,230
You could always rejoin your regiment.

540
01:38:39,330 --> 01:38:41,150
This is no time for flippancy, Higgins.

541
01:38:41,240 --> 01:38:43,280
The way you've driven her
the last six weeks...

542
01:38:43,370 --> 01:38:45,450
...has exceeded all bounds
of common decency.

543
01:38:45,540 --> 01:38:48,540
For God's sake, stop pacing.
Can't you settle somewhere?

544
01:38:48,630 --> 01:38:50,580
Have some port. It'll quieten your nerves.

545
01:38:50,670 --> 01:38:52,000
I'm not nervous.

546
01:38:53,630 --> 01:38:55,540
-Where is it?
-On the piano.

547
01:38:57,090 --> 01:38:58,420
The car's here, sir.

548
01:38:58,510 --> 01:39:00,170
Good. Tell Miss Doolittle.

549
01:39:00,260 --> 01:39:03,880
Tell Miss Doolittle indeed.
I'll bet you that damned gown doesn't fit.

550
01:39:03,970 --> 01:39:06,050
I warned you about these French designers.

551
01:39:06,140 --> 01:39:09,470
We should've gone to an English shop.
They would've been on our side.

552
01:39:09,560 --> 01:39:11,890
-Have a glass of port?
-No, thank you.

553
01:39:18,240 --> 01:39:22,450
Are you so sure this girl will retain
everything you've hammered into her?

554
01:39:23,030 --> 01:39:24,690
Well, we shall see.

555
01:39:25,030 --> 01:39:26,580
Suppose she doesn't?

556
01:39:27,830 --> 01:39:29,370
I lose my bet.

557
01:39:29,540 --> 01:39:33,200
There's one thing I can't stand about you,
your confounded complacency.

558
01:39:33,290 --> 01:39:35,330
At a moment like this,
with so much at stake...

559
01:39:35,420 --> 01:39:38,920
...it's utterly indecent
that you don't need a glass of port.

560
01:39:40,590 --> 01:39:44,340
And what about the girl? You act
as though she doesn't matter at all.

561
01:39:44,430 --> 01:39:47,050
Rubbish, Pickering. Of course she matters.

562
01:39:47,430 --> 01:39:49,840
What do you think I've been doing
all these months?

563
01:39:49,930 --> 01:39:53,430
What could possibly matter more
than to take a human being...

564
01:39:53,520 --> 01:39:57,730
...and change her into a different human
being by creating a new speech for her?

565
01:39:57,810 --> 01:40:01,560
It's filling up the deepest gap
that separates class from class...

566
01:40:01,730 --> 01:40:03,310
...and soul from soul.

567
01:40:03,740 --> 01:40:06,410
Oh, she matters immensely.

568
01:40:28,510 --> 01:40:31,000
Miss Doolittle, you look beautiful.

569
01:40:31,680 --> 01:40:33,260
Thank you, Colonel Pickering.

570
01:40:33,350 --> 01:40:35,260
Don't you think so, Higgins?

571
01:40:37,980 --> 01:40:40,650
Not bad. Not bad at all.

572
01:42:09,310 --> 01:42:11,770
Maestro! Maestro!

573
01:42:14,030 --> 01:42:15,190
Don't you remember me?

574
01:42:15,280 --> 01:42:16,900
No. Who the devil are you?

575
01:42:16,990 --> 01:42:20,440
I'm your pupil. Your first, your greatest,
your best pupil.

576
01:42:20,570 --> 01:42:23,060
I'm Zoltan Karpathy, that marvelous boy.

577
01:42:24,240 --> 01:42:26,200
I made your name famous
throughout Europe.

578
01:42:26,290 --> 01:42:28,200
You teach me phonetics.
You can't forget me.

579
01:42:28,290 --> 01:42:30,030
Why don't you have your hair cut?

580
01:42:30,120 --> 01:42:33,660
I don't have your imposing appearance,
your figure, your brow.

581
01:42:33,790 --> 01:42:35,830
If I had my hair cut,
nobody would notice me.

582
01:42:35,920 --> 01:42:37,750
Where did you get these old coins?

583
01:42:37,840 --> 01:42:39,830
These are decorations for languages.

584
01:42:39,920 --> 01:42:41,670
The Queen of Transylvania is here.

585
01:42:41,760 --> 01:42:44,880
I'm indispensable to her
at these official international parties.

586
01:42:44,970 --> 01:42:47,890
I speak 32 languages.
I know everyone in Europe.

587
01:42:47,970 --> 01:42:50,050
No imposter can escape my detection.

588
01:42:50,140 --> 01:42:52,130
Professor Karpathy.

589
01:42:54,310 --> 01:42:55,850
The Greek ambassador.

590
01:42:56,650 --> 01:42:57,730
Greek, my foot!

591
01:42:57,820 --> 01:43:00,600
He pretends not to know English,
but he can't deceive me.

592
01:43:00,690 --> 01:43:03,100
He's the son of a Yorkshire watchmaker.

593
01:43:03,820 --> 01:43:07,240
He speaks English so villainously
that he cannot utter a word...

594
01:43:07,320 --> 01:43:09,570
...without betraying his origin.

595
01:43:09,660 --> 01:43:13,410
I help him pretend, but make him pay
through the nose. I make them all pay.

596
01:43:13,500 --> 01:43:16,780
Excuse me, sir, you are wanted upstairs.
Her Excellency asked for you.

597
01:43:36,520 --> 01:43:38,510
Viscount and Viscountess Saxon.

598
01:43:41,900 --> 01:43:44,770
Baron and Baroness of Yorkshire.

599
01:43:46,490 --> 01:43:49,320
Sir Guy and Lady Scot-Auckland.

600
01:44:09,170 --> 01:44:11,330
The Count and Countess Demereau.

601
01:44:12,050 --> 01:44:14,540
The Viscount and Viscountess Hillyard.

602
01:44:14,720 --> 01:44:17,590
Mr. and Mrs. Richard Lanser.

603
01:44:18,220 --> 01:44:20,840
Lord and Lady Clanders.

604
01:44:21,520 --> 01:44:24,390
Miss Eliza Doolittle, Colonel Pickering.

605
01:44:24,730 --> 01:44:28,310
Miss Eliza Doolittle. Colonel Pickering.

606
01:44:28,730 --> 01:44:30,730
Professor Higgins.

607
01:44:31,240 --> 01:44:33,310
-Your Excellency.
-Miss Doolittle.

608
01:44:33,400 --> 01:44:34,680
How do you do?

609
01:44:34,780 --> 01:44:37,070
-Good evening, Colonel.
-Good evening.

610
01:44:38,490 --> 01:44:41,830
What an enchanting young lady
you have with you this evening.

611
01:44:41,910 --> 01:44:43,320
Well, who is she?

612
01:44:43,710 --> 01:44:47,410
Oh, a cousin of mine. And Higgins.
Excuse me.

613
01:44:47,750 --> 01:44:49,080
Professor Higgins.

614
01:44:49,170 --> 01:44:53,250
Such a faraway look,
as if she's always lived in a garden.

615
01:44:53,590 --> 01:44:55,750
So she has. A sort of garden.

616
01:45:24,620 --> 01:45:28,070
Henry must take Eliza home at once.
There's a language expert here.

617
01:45:28,160 --> 01:45:31,330
-Sort of, you know, '"imposterologist.'"
-I beg you pardon?

618
01:45:32,080 --> 01:45:34,620
The young lady with Colonel Pickering....

619
01:45:34,750 --> 01:45:36,330
Find out who she is.

620
01:45:36,590 --> 01:45:37,830
With pleasure.

621
01:45:38,300 --> 01:45:40,790
The whole situation is highly explosive.

622
01:45:46,600 --> 01:45:49,170
Tell me, Zoltan,
some more about the Greek ambassador.

623
01:45:49,270 --> 01:45:52,850
Gladly, but first I would love you
to present me to this glorious creature.

624
01:45:52,940 --> 01:45:55,140
Does he really come from Yorkshire?

625
01:46:03,990 --> 01:46:06,820
Her Majesty, the Queen of Transylvania...

626
01:46:07,120 --> 01:46:10,280
...and His Royal Highness Prince Gregor.

627
01:46:56,370 --> 01:46:58,860
Charming. Quite charming.

628
01:47:00,210 --> 01:47:02,000
Miss Doolittle, Madam.

629
01:48:38,090 --> 01:48:41,130
Miss Doolittle, my son would like
to dance with you.

1
01:49:36,710 --> 01:49:37,930
Eliza.

2
01:51:48,250 --> 01:51:50,070
Absolutely fantastic.

3
01:51:53,540 --> 01:51:55,000
A lot of tomfoolery.

4
01:51:55,080 --> 01:51:57,120
It was an immense achievement.

5
01:51:57,210 --> 01:51:58,670
Well, Mr. Higgins?

6
01:51:59,130 --> 01:52:02,250
A triumph, Mrs. Pearce. A total triumph.

7
01:52:02,550 --> 01:52:06,000
Higgins, you were superb,
absolutely superb.

8
01:52:06,220 --> 01:52:10,170
Tell us the truth now, weren't you
a little bit nervous once or twice?

9
01:52:10,310 --> 01:52:12,050
Not during the whole evening?

10
01:52:12,140 --> 01:52:13,800
Not when I saw we were going to win.

11
01:52:13,890 --> 01:52:15,890
I felt like a bear in a cage hanging about.

12
01:52:15,980 --> 01:52:17,640
It was an immense achievement.

13
01:52:17,730 --> 01:52:20,810
If I hadn't backed myself to do it,
I'd have given up two months ago.

14
01:52:20,900 --> 01:52:22,230
Absolutely fantastic.

15
01:52:22,320 --> 01:52:23,860
Yes, a lot of tomfoolery.

16
01:52:23,940 --> 01:52:25,900
Higgins, I salute you.

17
01:52:25,990 --> 01:52:28,740
The silly people don't know
their own silly business.

18
01:52:28,820 --> 01:52:31,830
'"Tonight, old man, you did it
You did it, you did it

19
01:52:31,990 --> 01:52:34,860
'"You said that you would do it
And indeed you did

20
01:52:34,960 --> 01:52:37,960
'"l thought that you would rue it
I doubted you'd do it

21
01:52:38,040 --> 01:52:41,000
'"But now I must admit it
That succeed you did

22
01:52:41,210 --> 01:52:43,830
'"You should get a medal
Or be even made a knight

23
01:52:43,920 --> 01:52:46,590
'"Oh, it was nothing, really nothing

24
01:52:47,300 --> 01:52:50,050
'"All alone you hurdled
Every obstacle in sight

25
01:52:50,300 --> 01:52:53,470
'"Now wait, now wait
Give credit where it's due

26
01:52:53,600 --> 01:52:56,090
'"A lot of the glory goes to you

27
01:52:56,810 --> 01:52:59,840
'"But you're the one who did it
Who did it, who did it

28
01:52:59,940 --> 01:53:02,850
'"As sturdy as Gibraltar
Not a second did you falter

29
01:53:02,940 --> 01:53:04,220
'"There's no doubt about it

30
01:53:04,320 --> 01:53:07,600
'"You did it!

31
01:53:10,820 --> 01:53:14,950
'"l must have aged a year tonight
At times I thought I'd die of fright

32
01:53:15,200 --> 01:53:17,910
'"Never was there a momentary lull

33
01:53:19,080 --> 01:53:23,080
'"Shortly after we came in
I saw at once we'd easily win

34
01:53:23,210 --> 01:53:25,960
'"And after that I found it deadly dull

35
01:53:27,250 --> 01:53:29,460
'"You should have heard
The 'oohs' and 'aahs'

36
01:53:29,550 --> 01:53:31,540
'"Everyone wondering who she was

37
01:53:31,630 --> 01:53:34,300
'"You'd think they'd never seen
a lady before

38
01:53:35,010 --> 01:53:39,340
'"And when the Prince of Transylvania
Asked to meet her

39
01:53:40,310 --> 01:53:43,810
'"And gave his arm to lead her to the floor

40
01:53:45,350 --> 01:53:48,640
'"l said to him: 'You did it
You did it, you did it'

41
01:53:48,730 --> 01:53:51,900
'"They thought she was ecstatic
And so damned aristocratic

42
01:53:51,980 --> 01:53:54,480
'"And they never knew
That you...

43
01:53:56,490 --> 01:53:57,650
'"...did it'"

44
01:53:59,870 --> 01:54:01,740
Thank goodness for Zoltan Karpathy.

45
01:54:01,830 --> 01:54:04,070
If it hadn't been for him
I would've died of boredom.

46
01:54:04,160 --> 01:54:06,400
Karpathy? That dreadful Hungarian?
Was he there?

47
01:54:06,500 --> 01:54:09,580
Yes, he was there all right
and up to his old tricks.

48
01:54:09,790 --> 01:54:12,250
'"That blackguard
Who uses the science of speech

49
01:54:12,340 --> 01:54:14,870
'"More to blackmail and swindle than teach

50
01:54:15,460 --> 01:54:17,960
'"He made it the devilish business of his

51
01:54:18,260 --> 01:54:21,260
'"To find out who this Miss Doolittle is

52
01:54:22,260 --> 01:54:24,720
'"Every time we looked around
There he was

53
01:54:24,850 --> 01:54:27,010
'"That hairy hound from Budapest

54
01:54:29,020 --> 01:54:32,020
'"Never leaving us alone
Never have I ever known

55
01:54:32,110 --> 01:54:33,390
'"A ruder pest

56
01:54:35,360 --> 01:54:39,600
'"Finally I decided it was foolish
Not to let him have his chance with her

57
01:54:41,660 --> 01:54:45,650
'"So I stepped aside
And let him dance with her

58
01:54:47,410 --> 01:54:52,540
'"Oozing charm from every pore
He oiled his way around the floor

59
01:54:52,870 --> 01:54:57,200
'"Every trick that he could play
He used to strip her mask away

60
01:54:57,670 --> 01:55:01,750
'"And when at last the dance was done
He glowed as if he knew he'd won

61
01:55:02,550 --> 01:55:05,670
'"And with a voice too eager
And a smile too broad

62
01:55:06,180 --> 01:55:09,680
'"He announced to the hostess
That she was a fraud'"

63
01:55:10,600 --> 01:55:11,880
No!

64
01:55:17,360 --> 01:55:21,770
'"'Her English is too good,' he said
'That clearly indicates that she is foreign

65
01:55:23,860 --> 01:55:26,650
'"'Whereas others are instructed
ln their native language

66
01:55:26,740 --> 01:55:28,530
'"'English people aren't

67
01:55:30,200 --> 01:55:34,860
'"'Although she may have studied with
an expert dialectician and grammarian

68
01:55:37,040 --> 01:55:41,700
'"'l can tell that she was born

69
01:55:43,130 --> 01:55:44,500
'"'Hungarian'

70
01:55:45,970 --> 01:55:48,420
'"Not only Hungarian but of royal blood

71
01:55:49,550 --> 01:55:51,540
'"She is a princess

72
01:55:51,890 --> 01:55:55,720
'"'Her blood,' he said
'ls bluer than the Danube is or ever was

73
01:55:55,850 --> 01:55:58,800
'"'Royalty is absolutely written on her face

74
01:55:58,890 --> 01:56:01,930
'"'She thought I was taken in
But actually I never was

75
01:56:02,060 --> 01:56:05,060
'"'How could she deceive
Another member of her race?

76
01:56:05,610 --> 01:56:09,990
'"'l know each language on the map'
Said he

77
01:56:10,240 --> 01:56:14,530
'"'And she's Hungarian
As the first Hungarian Rhapsody''"

78
01:56:22,540 --> 01:56:26,370
'"Congratulations, Professor Higgins

79
01:56:26,750 --> 01:56:30,250
'"For your glorious victory

80
01:56:30,510 --> 01:56:34,250
'"Congratulations, Professor Higgins

81
01:56:34,680 --> 01:56:38,130
'"You'll be mentioned in history'"

82
01:57:00,830 --> 01:57:03,030
Well, thank God, that's over.

83
01:57:03,580 --> 01:57:06,280
Now I can go to bed
without dreading tomorrow.

84
01:57:08,710 --> 01:57:11,030
-Good night, Mr. Higgins.
-Good night, Mrs. Pearce.

85
01:57:11,130 --> 01:57:14,990
I think I'll turn in, too. Good night.
It's been a great occasion.

86
01:57:15,090 --> 01:57:16,710
Good night, Pickering.

87
01:57:17,630 --> 01:57:18,960
Mrs. Pearce?

88
01:57:19,890 --> 01:57:24,100
Damn, I meant to ask her to give me coffee
in the morning instead of tea.

89
01:57:24,720 --> 01:57:28,560
Leave a little note for her will you, Eliza.
And put out the lights.

90
01:58:16,310 --> 01:58:18,890
Must be downstairs. Oh, darn it.

91
01:58:19,270 --> 01:58:21,100
I'll leave my head behind
one of these days.

92
01:58:21,190 --> 01:58:23,810
What the devil have I done
with my slippers?

93
01:58:26,530 --> 01:58:28,240
Here are your slippers!

94
01:58:33,540 --> 01:58:37,320
Take your slippers and may you never
have a day's luck with them.

95
01:58:38,040 --> 01:58:40,030
What on earth? What's the matter?

96
01:58:40,130 --> 01:58:41,790
Is anything wrong?

97
01:58:41,920 --> 01:58:44,870
No, nothing's wrong with you.
I won your bet for you, haven't l?

98
01:58:44,960 --> 01:58:47,840
That's enough for you!
I don't matter, I suppose?

99
01:58:48,430 --> 01:58:52,040
You won my bet?
You presumptuous insect! I won it!

100
01:58:52,140 --> 01:58:53,800
Why did you throw the slippers at me?

101
01:58:53,890 --> 01:58:57,340
Because I wanted to smash your face.
I could kill you, you selfish brute!

102
01:58:57,430 --> 01:58:59,590
Why didn't you leave me
where you picked me up?

103
01:58:59,690 --> 01:59:03,470
You thank God it's all over. Now you can
throw me back again! Do you?

104
01:59:03,570 --> 01:59:06,140
Oh, so the creature's nervous after all?

105
01:59:09,400 --> 01:59:11,980
Claws in, you cat!
How dare you show your temper to me?

106
01:59:12,070 --> 01:59:13,650
Sit down and be quiet!

107
01:59:13,740 --> 01:59:16,360
What's to become of me?

108
01:59:19,540 --> 01:59:21,450
How do I know what's to become of you?

109
01:59:21,540 --> 01:59:22,740
What does it matter?

110
01:59:22,830 --> 01:59:25,500
You don't care. I know you don't care.

111
01:59:25,590 --> 01:59:28,080
You wouldn't care if I was dead.
I'm nothing to you.

112
01:59:28,170 --> 01:59:30,040
Not as much as them slippers.

113
01:59:30,130 --> 01:59:31,210
Those slippers!

114
01:59:31,300 --> 01:59:34,960
Those slippers! I didn't think it meant
any difference now.

115
01:59:38,560 --> 01:59:41,310
Why have you suddenly begun
going on like this?

116
01:59:41,640 --> 01:59:44,310
May I ask if you complain
of your treatment here?

117
01:59:44,390 --> 01:59:45,220
No.

118
01:59:45,350 --> 01:59:48,470
Has anybody behaved badly?
Colonel Pickering, Mrs. Pearce?

119
01:59:48,570 --> 01:59:49,600
No.

120
01:59:49,900 --> 01:59:52,980
Well you don't pretend
that I have treated you badly?

121
01:59:53,780 --> 01:59:54,810
No.

122
01:59:54,900 --> 01:59:56,810
Well, I'm glad to hear that.

123
01:59:57,820 --> 02:00:00,690
Perhaps you're tired
after the strain of the day.

124
02:00:01,370 --> 02:00:03,740
Would you have a chocolate?

125
02:00:04,080 --> 02:00:06,570
No, thank you.

126
02:00:08,750 --> 02:00:12,750
Well, it's only natural that you should
be anxious, but it's all over now.

127
02:00:12,840 --> 02:00:14,710
Nothing more to worry about.

128
02:00:14,800 --> 02:00:17,670
No, nothing more for you to worry about.

129
02:00:19,010 --> 02:00:21,710
Oh, God, I wish I was dead.

130
02:00:22,350 --> 02:00:24,920
Why? ln heaven's name, why?

131
02:00:25,770 --> 02:00:29,510
Now listen to me, Eliza.
All this irritation is purely subjective.

132
02:00:29,900 --> 02:00:32,140
I don't understand. I'm too ignorant.

133
02:00:32,230 --> 02:00:35,730
It's just imagination. Nothing's wrong.
Nobody's hurting you.

134
02:00:35,820 --> 02:00:37,020
Go to bed and sleep it off.

135
02:00:37,110 --> 02:00:41,570
Have a little cry and say your prayers.
You'll feel very much more comfortable.

136
02:00:41,910 --> 02:00:43,730
I heard your prayers.

137
02:00:43,910 --> 02:00:45,650
'"Thank God it's all over.'"

138
02:00:45,780 --> 02:00:47,490
Don't you thank God it's all over?

139
02:00:47,580 --> 02:00:49,990
Now you're free,
and you can do what you like.

140
02:00:50,080 --> 02:00:53,200
Oh, what am I fit for?
What have you left me fit for?

141
02:00:53,920 --> 02:00:56,670
Where am I to go? What am I to do?

142
02:00:57,300 --> 02:00:59,370
And what's to become of me?

143
02:01:00,470 --> 02:01:03,300
That's what's worrying you, is it?

144
02:01:04,930 --> 02:01:06,880
I wouldn't worry about that if I were you.

145
02:01:06,970 --> 02:01:11,380
I'm sure you won't have any difficulty
in settling yourself somewhere or other.

146
02:01:14,140 --> 02:01:16,770
I didn't quite realize you were going away.

147
02:01:17,810 --> 02:01:19,770
You might marry, you know.

148
02:01:20,150 --> 02:01:24,060
You see, Eliza, all men are not confirmed
old bachelors like me and the Colonel.

149
02:01:24,150 --> 02:01:27,150
Most men are the marrying sort,
poor devils.

150
02:01:27,910 --> 02:01:28,900
You're not bad-looking.

151
02:01:28,990 --> 02:01:31,480
You're really quite a pleasure
to look at sometimes.

152
02:01:31,580 --> 02:01:33,120
Not now, when you've been crying.

153
02:01:33,200 --> 02:01:35,000
You look like the very devil, but...

154
02:01:35,080 --> 02:01:39,540
...when you're all right and quite yourself
you're what I would call attractive.

155
02:01:41,460 --> 02:01:43,790
Go to bed, have a good rest,
get up in the morning...

156
02:01:43,880 --> 02:01:47,660
...and have a look at yourself in the glass.
You won't feel so bad.

157
02:01:52,140 --> 02:01:55,970
I daresay, my mother might find some
fellow or other who would do very well.

158
02:01:56,060 --> 02:01:58,180
We were above that at Covent Garden.

159
02:01:58,270 --> 02:01:59,730
What do you mean?

160
02:01:59,940 --> 02:02:02,470
I sold flowers, I didn't sell myself.

161
02:02:03,230 --> 02:02:06,350
Now you've made a lady of me,
I'm not fit to sell anything else.

162
02:02:06,440 --> 02:02:09,110
Oh, tosh, Eliza.
Don't insult human relations...

163
02:02:09,200 --> 02:02:12,230
...by dragging all that cant
about buying and selling into it.

164
02:02:12,320 --> 02:02:14,400
Don't marry the fellow if you don't want to.

165
02:02:14,490 --> 02:02:16,120
What else am I to do?

166
02:02:16,200 --> 02:02:18,030
Oh, there are lots of things.

167
02:02:18,120 --> 02:02:20,530
What about the old idea of a florist shop?

168
02:02:20,620 --> 02:02:23,660
I'm sure Pickering'd set you up in one.
He's got lots of money.

169
02:02:23,750 --> 02:02:25,710
He'll pay for all those togs you're wearing.

170
02:02:25,790 --> 02:02:29,870
And that with the hire of the jewelry'll
make a big hole in 200 pounds.

171
02:02:30,090 --> 02:02:32,460
Come on now. You'll be all right.

172
02:02:33,630 --> 02:02:36,800
Well, I must be off to bed.
I'm really devilish sleepy.

173
02:02:38,140 --> 02:02:40,430
I was looking for something. What was it?

174
02:02:40,520 --> 02:02:41,710
Your slippers.

175
02:02:42,230 --> 02:02:44,980
Oh, yes, of course. You shied them at me.

176
02:02:46,100 --> 02:02:48,390
Before you go, sir.

177
02:02:52,150 --> 02:02:55,150
Do my clothes belong to me
or to Colonel Pickering?

178
02:02:56,240 --> 02:02:58,450
What the devil use would they be
to Pickering?

179
02:02:58,530 --> 02:03:00,530
Why bother about that
in the middle of the night?

180
02:03:00,620 --> 02:03:02,080
What may I take away with me?

181
02:03:02,160 --> 02:03:04,570
I don't want to be accused of stealing.

182
02:03:05,250 --> 02:03:06,330
Stealing?

183
02:03:07,420 --> 02:03:10,700
You shouldn't have said that.
That shows a want of feeling.

184
02:03:10,790 --> 02:03:14,840
I'm sorry. I'm a common, ignorant girl
and in my station I have to be careful.

185
02:03:14,920 --> 02:03:18,370
There can't be any feelings between
the likes of you and the likes of me.

186
02:03:18,470 --> 02:03:21,970
Please, will you tell me
what belongs to me and what doesn't?

187
02:03:22,430 --> 02:03:24,800
Take the whole damned houseful
if you want.

188
02:03:24,890 --> 02:03:27,640
Except the jewelry. That's hired.
Will that satisfy you?

189
02:03:27,730 --> 02:03:28,970
Stop, please.

190
02:03:31,190 --> 02:03:34,220
Will you take these to your room
and keep them safe?

191
02:03:35,070 --> 02:03:37,980
I don't want to run the risk
of them being missed.

192
02:03:39,570 --> 02:03:43,070
Hand them over! lf these belonged
to me and not the jeweler, I'd...

193
02:03:43,160 --> 02:03:45,730
...l'd ram them down
your ungrateful throat.

194
02:03:46,040 --> 02:03:50,120
The ring isn't the jeweler's.
It's the one you bought me in Brighton.

195
02:03:51,460 --> 02:03:53,000
I don't want it now.

196
02:03:56,250 --> 02:03:57,910
Don't you hit me!

197
02:03:58,420 --> 02:04:01,590
Hit you? You infamous creature!
How dare you suggest such a thing!

198
02:04:01,670 --> 02:04:04,340
It's you who've hit me.
You've wounded me to the heart.

199
02:04:04,430 --> 02:04:08,010
I'm glad. I've got a little
of my own back anyhow.

200
02:04:09,180 --> 02:04:12,760
You've caused me to lose my temper.
That's hardly happened to me before.

201
02:04:12,850 --> 02:04:15,640
I don't wish to discuss it further tonight.
I'm going to bed.

202
02:04:15,730 --> 02:04:18,300
Leave your own note for Mrs. Pearce
about the coffee...

203
02:04:18,400 --> 02:04:19,980
...for it won't be done by me!

204
02:04:20,070 --> 02:04:23,650
Damn Mrs. Pearce,
damn the coffee and damn you!

205
02:04:24,900 --> 02:04:28,150
Damn my own folly for having lavished
my hard-earned knowledge...

206
02:04:28,240 --> 02:04:32,400
...and the treasure of my regard
and intimacy on a heartless guttersnipe!

207
02:05:23,670 --> 02:05:28,290
'"Just you wait, 'Enry 'lggins
Just you wait!

208
02:05:30,260 --> 02:05:34,500
'"You'll be sorry
But your tears will be too late

209
02:05:36,510 --> 02:05:39,380
'"You will be the one it's done to

210
02:05:40,180 --> 02:05:43,430
'"And you'll have no one to run to

211
02:05:44,020 --> 02:05:45,600
'"Just you wait'"

212
02:06:14,300 --> 02:06:19,040
'"l have often walked
down this street before

213
02:06:20,050 --> 02:06:24,880
'"But the pavement always stayed
beneath my feet before

214
02:06:25,810 --> 02:06:30,850
'"All at once am I several stories high

215
02:06:31,650 --> 02:06:36,190
'"Knowing I'm on the street where you live

216
02:06:37,650 --> 02:06:42,400
'"Are there lilac trees in the heart of town?

217
02:06:43,490 --> 02:06:48,400
'"Can you hear a lark
in any other part of town?

218
02:06:49,500 --> 02:06:54,660
'"Does enchantment pour
out of every door?

219
02:06:55,420 --> 02:06:59,960
'"No, it's just on the street where you live

220
02:07:01,470 --> 02:07:06,090
'"And, oh, the towering feeling

221
02:07:07,010 --> 02:07:11,760
'"Just to know somehow you are near

222
02:07:13,350 --> 02:07:17,760
'"The overpowering feeling

223
02:07:18,440 --> 02:07:23,350
'"That any second you may suddenly appear

224
02:07:24,820 --> 02:07:28,070
'"People stop and stare, they don't....'"

225
02:07:34,830 --> 02:07:35,860
Darling.

226
02:07:37,290 --> 02:07:39,030
Freddy, whatever are you doing here?

227
02:07:39,130 --> 02:07:42,990
Nothing. I spend most of my nights here.
It's the only place where I'm happy.

228
02:07:43,090 --> 02:07:44,710
Don't laugh at me, Miss Doolittle.

229
02:07:44,800 --> 02:07:49,130
Don't you call me '"Miss Doolittle,'"
do you hear? Eliza's good enough for me.

230
02:07:51,050 --> 02:07:54,640
Freddy, you don't think
I'm a heartless guttersnipe, do you?

231
02:07:54,720 --> 02:07:57,810
Darling, how could you imagine
such a thing? You know how I feel.

232
02:07:57,890 --> 02:08:01,340
I've written two and three times a day
telling you. Sheets and sheets.

233
02:08:01,440 --> 02:08:04,810
'"Speak, and the world is full of singing

234
02:08:04,980 --> 02:08:09,060
'"And I am winging higher than the birds

235
02:08:10,410 --> 02:08:13,860
'"Touch, and my heart begins to crumble

236
02:08:14,240 --> 02:08:18,070
'"The heavens tumble
Darling, and I'm--'"

237
02:08:18,200 --> 02:08:21,200
'"Words, words, words
I'm so sick of words

238
02:08:21,370 --> 02:08:24,540
'"l get words all day through
First from him, now from you

239
02:08:24,630 --> 02:08:27,830
'"ls that all you blighters can do?

240
02:08:29,460 --> 02:08:32,380
'"Don't talk of stars burning above

241
02:08:32,800 --> 02:08:35,290
'"lf you're in love, show me

242
02:08:36,140 --> 02:08:39,140
'"Tell me no dreams filled with desire

243
02:08:39,470 --> 02:08:41,930
'"lf you're on fire, show me

244
02:08:42,690 --> 02:08:45,060
'"Here we are together
ln the middle of the night

245
02:08:45,150 --> 02:08:48,430
'"Don't talk of spring
Just hold me tight

246
02:08:49,230 --> 02:08:51,560
'"Anyone who's ever been in love'll
Tell you that

247
02:08:51,650 --> 02:08:53,610
'"This is no time for a chat

248
02:08:55,820 --> 02:08:58,690
'"Haven't your lips longed for my touch?

249
02:08:59,200 --> 02:09:01,570
'"Don't say how much, show me

250
02:09:02,290 --> 02:09:03,830
'"Show me

251
02:09:04,210 --> 02:09:07,320
'"Don't talk of love lasting through time

252
02:09:07,670 --> 02:09:10,200
'"Make me no undying vow

253
02:09:10,960 --> 02:09:15,120
'"Show me now

254
02:09:17,590 --> 02:09:20,590
'"Sing me no song, read me no rhyme

255
02:09:20,890 --> 02:09:23,720
'"Don't waste my time, show me

256
02:09:24,350 --> 02:09:27,680
'"Don't talk of June, don't talk of fall

257
02:09:27,770 --> 02:09:30,690
'"Don't talk at all, show me

258
02:09:31,190 --> 02:09:33,480
'"Never do I ever
want to hear another word

259
02:09:33,570 --> 02:09:37,060
'"There isn't one I haven't heard

260
02:09:37,820 --> 02:09:40,280
'"Here we are together
in what ought to be a dream

261
02:09:40,360 --> 02:09:43,860
'"Say one more word and I'll scream

262
02:09:44,580 --> 02:09:47,610
'"Haven't your arms hungered for mine?

263
02:09:48,000 --> 02:09:50,370
'"Please don't explain, show me

264
02:09:51,120 --> 02:09:52,700
'"Show me

265
02:09:53,130 --> 02:09:56,080
'"Don't wait until wrinkles and lines

266
02:09:56,500 --> 02:09:59,370
'"Pop out all over my brow

267
02:09:59,880 --> 02:10:04,210
'"Show me now! '"

268
02:10:08,640 --> 02:10:10,380
-Where are you going?
-To the river.

269
02:10:10,470 --> 02:10:12,550
-What for?
-To make a hole in it.

270
02:10:14,100 --> 02:10:16,260
Eliza, darling, what do you mean?

271
02:10:25,820 --> 02:10:27,900
Taxi!

272
02:10:28,580 --> 02:10:30,530
-But I've no money.
-I have.

273
02:10:30,870 --> 02:10:33,080
-Where are we going?
-Where I belong.

274
02:10:47,930 --> 02:10:49,970
Darling, shall I come with you?

275
02:11:16,450 --> 02:11:19,950
''With one enormous chair

276
02:11:20,080 --> 02:11:24,290
''Oh, wouldn't it be loverly?

277
02:11:25,630 --> 02:11:29,840
''Lots of chocolate for me to eat

278
02:11:30,630 --> 02:11:34,930
''Lots of coal makin' lots of 'eat

279
02:11:36,180 --> 02:11:39,800
''Warm face, warm 'ands, warm feet

280
02:11:39,930 --> 02:11:44,260
''Oh, wouldn't it be loverly?''

281
02:11:47,230 --> 02:11:48,730
Buy a flower, miss?

282
02:11:50,150 --> 02:11:51,350
Yes, please.

283
02:12:28,440 --> 02:12:30,680
Good morning, miss. Can I help you?

284
02:12:34,020 --> 02:12:36,060
Do you mind if I warm my hands?

285
02:12:36,190 --> 02:12:37,770
Go right ahead, miss.

286
02:12:46,370 --> 02:12:49,240
Excuse me. For a second
I thought you were somebody else.

287
02:12:49,330 --> 02:12:50,330
Who?

288
02:12:50,920 --> 02:12:54,620
Forgive me, ma'am. Early morning light
playing tricks with my eyes.

289
02:12:54,710 --> 02:12:57,630
Can I get you a taxi?
A lady shouldn't be walkin' alone...

290
02:12:57,710 --> 02:13:00,290
...around London this hour of the morning.

291
02:13:01,880 --> 02:13:03,290
No, thank you.

292
02:13:12,770 --> 02:13:16,600
''Someone's head restin' on my knee

293
02:13:17,110 --> 02:13:20,810
''Warm and tender as he can be

294
02:13:22,030 --> 02:13:25,190
''Who takes good care of me

295
02:13:25,490 --> 02:13:29,150
''Oh, wouldn't it...

296
02:13:29,910 --> 02:13:31,740
''...be loverly?

297
02:13:33,250 --> 02:13:35,650
''Loverly ''

298
02:13:49,760 --> 02:13:53,970
Do come again, Mr. Doolittle.
We value your patronage always.

299
02:13:54,060 --> 02:13:57,090
Thank you, my good man. Thank you.
Here. Come 'ere.

300
02:13:57,890 --> 02:14:00,470
Take the missus on a trip to Brighton
with my compliments.

301
02:14:00,560 --> 02:14:02,390
Thank you, Mr. Doolittle.

302
02:14:03,690 --> 02:14:06,860
Jolly spot this, Harry.
We must visit it more often.

303
02:14:07,860 --> 02:14:08,810
Father?

304
02:14:11,070 --> 02:14:14,410
Oh, no. You see, Harry, he has no mercy.

305
02:14:14,700 --> 02:14:18,780
Sent her down to spy on me in me misery,
he did. Me own flesh and blood.

306
02:14:21,750 --> 02:14:24,830
Well, I'm miserable, all right.
You can tell him that straight.

307
02:14:24,920 --> 02:14:27,590
What are you talking about?
What are you dressed up for?

308
02:14:27,670 --> 02:14:29,080
As if you didn't know.

309
02:14:29,170 --> 02:14:33,170
Go on back to that Wimpole Street devil.
Tell him what he's done to me.

310
02:14:33,390 --> 02:14:35,010
What's he done to you?

311
02:14:35,430 --> 02:14:36,670
Ruined me, that's all.

312
02:14:36,760 --> 02:14:40,600
Tied me up and delivered me
into the hands of middle-class morality.

313
02:14:41,020 --> 02:14:42,390
And don't you defend him.

314
02:14:42,480 --> 02:14:47,020
Was it 'im or was it not 'im wrote to an old
American blighter named Wallingford...

315
02:14:47,110 --> 02:14:51,270
...who was giving $5,000,000
to found Moral Reform societies...

316
02:14:51,780 --> 02:14:56,360
...to tell him the most original moralist
in England was Mr. Alfred P. Doolittle...

317
02:14:56,450 --> 02:14:57,990
...a common dustman?

318
02:14:59,490 --> 02:15:01,450
Sounds like one of his jokes.

319
02:15:01,620 --> 02:15:04,820
You may call it a joke.
It's put the lid on me. Proper.

320
02:15:05,120 --> 02:15:09,370
The old bloke died and left me
4,000 pounds a year in his bloomin' will.

321
02:15:10,790 --> 02:15:14,920
Who asked him to make a gentleman
outta me? I was 'appy. I was free.

322
02:15:15,510 --> 02:15:19,720
I touched pretty nigh everyone for money
when I wanted it, same as I touched him.

323
02:15:19,800 --> 02:15:23,420
Now I'm tied neck and 'eels
and everybody touches me.

324
02:15:24,140 --> 02:15:27,010
A year ago I 'adn't a relation in the world...

325
02:15:27,730 --> 02:15:29,800
...except one or two
who wouldn't speak to me.

326
02:15:29,900 --> 02:15:33,510
Now I've 50. Not a decent week's wages
amongst the lot of them.

327
02:15:34,150 --> 02:15:38,810
I have to live for others now,
not for meself. Middle-class morality.

328
02:15:39,530 --> 02:15:42,860
Come on, Alfie, in a few hours
we have to be at the church.

329
02:15:42,950 --> 02:15:45,160
-Church?
-Yeah, church.

330
02:15:46,160 --> 02:15:48,070
The deepest cut of all.

331
02:15:48,580 --> 02:15:51,780
Why do you think I'm dressed up
like a ruddy pallbearer?

332
02:15:52,330 --> 02:15:54,240
Your stepmother wants to marry me.

333
02:15:54,340 --> 02:15:57,170
Now I'm respectable,
she wants to be respectable.

334
02:15:57,460 --> 02:16:00,830
If that's the way you feel,
why don't you give the money back?

335
02:16:00,920 --> 02:16:03,000
That's the tragedy of it, Eliza.

336
02:16:03,260 --> 02:16:05,130
It's easy to say chuck it...

337
02:16:05,970 --> 02:16:07,800
...but I 'aven't the nerve.

338
02:16:08,140 --> 02:16:10,760
We're all intimidated.
That's what we are, intimidated.

339
02:16:10,850 --> 02:16:13,520
Bought up. Yeah. That's what I am.

340
02:16:14,270 --> 02:16:16,940
That's what your precious professor's
brought me to.

341
02:16:17,020 --> 02:16:19,020
Not my precious professor.

342
02:16:19,730 --> 02:16:21,640
Oh, sent you back, 'as he?

343
02:16:23,320 --> 02:16:28,230
First he shoves me in the middle-class,
then he chucks you out for me to support.

344
02:16:28,870 --> 02:16:30,860
That's all part of his plan...

345
02:16:31,490 --> 02:16:33,400
...but you double-cross him.

346
02:16:34,000 --> 02:16:38,160
Don't you come back home to me.
Don't you take tuppence from me.

347
02:16:38,750 --> 02:16:42,290
You stand on your own two feet.
You're a lady now, you can do it.

348
02:16:42,380 --> 02:16:45,330
Yeah, that's right, Eliza.
You're a lady now.

349
02:16:46,010 --> 02:16:48,080
It's getting awfully cold in that taxi.

350
02:16:48,180 --> 02:16:52,300
Here, Eliza, would you like to come
and see me turned off this morning?

351
02:16:52,390 --> 02:16:54,960
St. George's, Hanover Square, 10:00.

352
02:16:55,100 --> 02:16:57,140
I wouldn't advise it, but you're welcome.

353
02:16:57,230 --> 02:16:58,720
No, thank you, Dad.

354
02:16:59,900 --> 02:17:02,050
Are you all finished here, Eliza?

355
02:17:02,650 --> 02:17:05,650
Yes, Freddy, I'm all finished here.

356
02:17:09,570 --> 02:17:10,850
Good luck, Dad.

357
02:17:11,240 --> 02:17:12,650
Thank you, Eliza.

358
02:17:30,420 --> 02:17:31,460
Come along, Alfie.

359
02:17:31,550 --> 02:17:33,340
How much time have I got left?

360
02:17:33,430 --> 02:17:36,260
'"There's just a few more hours

361
02:17:36,470 --> 02:17:38,840
'"That's all the time you've got

362
02:17:38,930 --> 02:17:41,340
'"A few more hours

363
02:17:41,600 --> 02:17:43,970
'"Before they tie the knot'"

364
02:17:44,940 --> 02:17:47,890
There's drinks and girls all over London.

365
02:17:48,270 --> 02:17:52,060
And I gotta track 'em down
in just a few more hours.

366
02:17:52,900 --> 02:17:54,610
Set 'em up, me darlin'.

367
02:17:55,200 --> 02:17:58,650
'"l'm gettin' married in the mornin'

368
02:17:59,580 --> 02:18:02,700
'"Ding dong, the bells are gonna chime

369
02:18:03,750 --> 02:18:07,410
'"Pull out the stopper
Let's have a whopper

370
02:18:07,670 --> 02:18:10,870
'"But get me to the church on time

371
02:18:12,170 --> 02:18:15,420
'"l got to be there in the mornin'

372
02:18:16,340 --> 02:18:19,260
'"Spruced up and looking in me prime

373
02:18:20,510 --> 02:18:24,260
'"Girls, come and kiss me
Show how you'll miss me

374
02:18:24,350 --> 02:18:27,390
'"But get me to the church on time

375
02:18:28,060 --> 02:18:31,930
'"lf I am dancin'
Roll up the floor

376
02:18:32,270 --> 02:18:36,190
'"lf I am whistlin'
Me out the door

377
02:18:37,240 --> 02:18:40,610
'"For I'm getting married in the mornin'

378
02:18:41,450 --> 02:18:44,480
'"Ding dong, the bells are gonna chime

379
02:18:45,700 --> 02:18:49,240
'"Kick up a rumpus
But don't lose the compass

380
02:18:49,460 --> 02:18:51,360
'"And get me to the church

381
02:18:53,710 --> 02:18:56,630
'"For God's sake
Get me to the church...

382
02:18:57,130 --> 02:18:59,250
'"...on time

383
02:19:02,510 --> 02:19:05,710
'"l'm gettin' married in the mornin'

384
02:19:06,390 --> 02:19:09,510
'"Ding dong, the bells are gonna chime

385
02:19:10,310 --> 02:19:13,760
'"Some bloke who's able
Lift up the table

386
02:19:14,060 --> 02:19:17,150
'"But get me to the church on time

387
02:19:17,440 --> 02:19:20,690
'"lf I am flyin'
Then shoot me down

388
02:19:21,400 --> 02:19:24,940
'"lf I am wooin'
Get her out of town

389
02:19:25,610 --> 02:19:29,310
'"For I'm getting married in the mornin'

390
02:19:29,990 --> 02:19:33,030
'"Ding dong, the bells are gonna chime

391
02:19:34,160 --> 02:19:37,700
'"Feather and tar me
Call out the Army

392
02:19:37,830 --> 02:19:39,830
'"But get me to the church

393
02:19:40,130 --> 02:19:41,710
'"Get me to the church

394
02:19:42,050 --> 02:19:44,960
'"For God's sake
Get me to the church...

395
02:19:45,050 --> 02:19:47,120
'"...on time

396
02:19:47,970 --> 02:19:50,970
'"He's gettin' married in the mornin'

397
02:19:51,890 --> 02:19:54,890
'"Ding dong, the bells are gonna chime

398
02:19:55,390 --> 02:19:59,440
'"Come on, pull out the stopper
Let's have a whopper

399
02:19:59,690 --> 02:20:03,140
'"But get me to the church on time

400
02:20:03,860 --> 02:20:06,980
'"He's got to be there in the mornin'

401
02:20:07,950 --> 02:20:10,730
'"Spruced up and lookin' in his prime

402
02:20:12,030 --> 02:20:15,650
'"Girls, come and kiss me
Show how you'll miss me

403
02:20:15,790 --> 02:20:18,870
'"But get me to the church on time

404
02:20:19,290 --> 02:20:23,040
'"lf I am dancin'
Roll up the floor

405
02:20:23,380 --> 02:20:27,370
'"lf I am whistlin'
Me out the door

406
02:20:36,100 --> 02:20:39,760
'"Drug me or jail me
Stamp me and mail me

407
02:20:39,980 --> 02:20:41,800
'"But get me to the church

408
02:20:42,060 --> 02:20:43,680
'"Get him to the church

409
02:20:43,900 --> 02:20:48,770
'"For God's sake
Get me to the church on time

410
02:20:58,410 --> 02:21:01,990
'"Girls come and kiss him
Show how they miss him

411
02:21:02,160 --> 02:21:05,250
'"But get him to the church on time

412
02:21:14,590 --> 02:21:18,040
'"Kick up a rumpus
But don't lose the compass

413
02:21:18,300 --> 02:21:21,510
'"And get him to the church on time

414
02:21:22,100 --> 02:21:25,430
'"lf I am flyin'
Then shoot me down

415
02:21:25,930 --> 02:21:29,550
'"lf I am wooin'
Get her out of town

416
02:21:30,610 --> 02:21:33,860
'"He's gettin' married in the mornin'

417
02:21:34,690 --> 02:21:37,810
'"Ding dong, the bells are gonna chime

418
02:21:38,780 --> 02:21:42,440
'"Some bloke who's able
Lift up the table

419
02:21:42,620 --> 02:21:45,950
'"But get me to the church on time

420
02:22:23,450 --> 02:22:28,320
'"Starlight is reelin'
Home to bed now

421
02:22:30,450 --> 02:22:35,030
'"Mornin' is smearin' up the sky

422
02:22:37,540 --> 02:22:40,000
'"London is wakin'

423
02:22:40,880 --> 02:22:43,420
'"Daylight is breakin'

424
02:22:44,300 --> 02:22:46,290
'"Good luck, old chum

425
02:22:47,010 --> 02:22:49,000
'"Good health

426
02:22:49,090 --> 02:22:51,630
'"Goodbye

427
02:22:54,220 --> 02:22:59,650
'"l'm gettin' married in the mornin'

428
02:23:02,320 --> 02:23:07,270
'"Ding dong, the bells are gonna chime

429
02:23:08,860 --> 02:23:12,940
'"Hail and salute me
Then haul off and boot me

430
02:23:13,200 --> 02:23:17,030
'"But get him to the church
Get him to the church

431
02:23:17,580 --> 02:23:21,530
'"For God's sake
Get him to the church...

432
02:23:21,620 --> 02:23:23,620
'"...on time'"

433
02:23:34,510 --> 02:23:36,590
Didn't she say where to send her clothes?

434
02:23:36,680 --> 02:23:39,350
I told you, sir, she took them all with her.

435
02:23:39,520 --> 02:23:42,350
Here's a confounded thing. Eliza's bolted.

436
02:23:42,440 --> 02:23:45,690
Last night Mrs. Pearce let her go
without telling me about it!

437
02:23:45,770 --> 02:23:48,310
What'll I do? I got tea this morning
instead of coffee.

438
02:23:48,400 --> 02:23:51,070
I don't know where anything is,
what my appointments are.

439
02:23:51,150 --> 02:23:52,940
-Eliza'd know.
-Damn it, she's gone!

440
02:23:53,030 --> 02:23:55,150
Did either of you frighten her last night?

441
02:23:55,240 --> 02:23:57,450
We hardly said a word to her.
You were there.

442
02:23:57,530 --> 02:23:59,360
Did you bully her after I went to bed?

443
02:23:59,450 --> 02:24:00,830
She threw the slippers at me.

444
02:24:00,910 --> 02:24:02,820
I never gave her the slightest provocation.

445
02:24:02,910 --> 02:24:05,400
The slippers came at my head
before I uttered a word.

446
02:24:05,500 --> 02:24:09,370
She used the most disgraceful language.
I was shocked! I don't understand.

447
02:24:09,460 --> 02:24:12,130
We always gave her every consideration.
She admitted it.

448
02:24:12,210 --> 02:24:13,080
I'm dashed!

449
02:24:13,170 --> 02:24:16,710
Pickering, for God's sake,
stop being dashed and do something!

450
02:24:16,800 --> 02:24:19,420
Phone the police. What are they there for?

451
02:24:19,510 --> 02:24:22,000
You can't give Eliza's name to the police...

452
02:24:22,100 --> 02:24:24,220
...as if she were a thief or a lost umbrella.

453
02:24:24,310 --> 02:24:26,220
But why not? I want to find the girl.

454
02:24:26,310 --> 02:24:29,010
She belongs to me.
I paid five pounds for her.

455
02:24:29,270 --> 02:24:31,940
Quite right. Hello. Scotland Yard, please?

456
02:24:32,270 --> 02:24:34,600
Get me some coffee, would you please?

457
02:24:35,440 --> 02:24:36,690
Scotland Yard?

458
02:24:37,400 --> 02:24:41,320
This is Colonel Pickering speaking.

459
02:24:42,410 --> 02:24:45,080
27A Wimpole Street.

460
02:24:45,580 --> 02:24:47,820
I want to report a missing person.

461
02:24:48,500 --> 02:24:50,790
Miss Eliza Doolittle.

462
02:24:51,790 --> 02:24:52,870
About 21 .

463
02:24:53,960 --> 02:24:56,830
I should say about 5 foot 7.

464
02:24:58,090 --> 02:25:02,040
Her eyes? Let me think now. Her eyes....

465
02:25:02,380 --> 02:25:04,130
-Brown.
-Brown.

466
02:25:06,890 --> 02:25:11,600
Her hair? Good Lord.
Sort of a nondescript neutral sort of--

467
02:25:11,690 --> 02:25:13,310
Brown, brown, brown!

468
02:25:13,440 --> 02:25:16,110
You heard what he said?
Brown, brown, brown, yes.

469
02:25:16,190 --> 02:25:18,680
No. This is her residence. 27A--

470
02:25:18,780 --> 02:25:22,560
Yes, about between 3:00 and 4:00
this morning, I understand.

471
02:25:23,740 --> 02:25:26,820
No.... She's no relation, no.

472
02:25:27,780 --> 02:25:30,700
Well, let's call her a good friend, shall we?

473
02:25:31,160 --> 02:25:32,620
I beg your pardon?

474
02:25:32,750 --> 02:25:35,500
Listen to me, I don't like the tenor
of that question.

475
02:25:35,580 --> 02:25:37,950
What the girl does here is our affair.

476
02:25:39,250 --> 02:25:42,700
Your affair is to get her back
so she can continue doing it.

477
02:25:43,340 --> 02:25:44,830
Well, I'm dashed!

478
02:25:47,380 --> 02:25:50,390
'"What in heaven
could have prompted her to go?

479
02:25:50,470 --> 02:25:52,630
'"After such a triumph at the ball

480
02:25:53,470 --> 02:25:55,020
'"What could have depressed her?

481
02:25:55,100 --> 02:25:59,050
'"What could have possessed her?
I cannot understand the wretch at all'"

482
02:26:01,230 --> 02:26:05,360
Higgins, I have an old school chum
at the Home Office. Perhaps he could help.

483
02:26:05,440 --> 02:26:07,270
Think I'll give him a ring.

484
02:26:08,820 --> 02:26:11,530
Whitehall: 7244, please.

485
02:26:14,200 --> 02:26:16,870
'"Women are irrational
That's all there is to that

486
02:26:16,950 --> 02:26:19,620
'"Their heads are full of
Cotton, hay and rags

487
02:26:20,040 --> 02:26:23,790
'"They're nothing but exasperating
lrritating, vacillating, calculating

488
02:26:23,880 --> 02:26:26,630
'"Agitating, maddening
And infuriating hags'"

489
02:26:28,170 --> 02:26:31,340
I want to speak
to Mr. Brewster Budgin, please.

490
02:26:32,300 --> 02:26:33,710
Yes, I'll wait.

491
02:26:39,100 --> 02:26:43,140
Pickering, why can't a woman
be more like a man?

492
02:26:44,020 --> 02:26:45,480
I beg your pardon?

493
02:26:45,730 --> 02:26:49,020
Yes, why can't a woman
be more like a man?

494
02:26:49,900 --> 02:26:52,610
'"Men are so honest, so thoroughly square

495
02:26:53,030 --> 02:26:55,780
'"Eternally noble, historically fair

496
02:26:56,450 --> 02:26:59,490
'"Who, when you win
Will always give your back a pat?

497
02:26:59,870 --> 02:27:02,160
'"Why can't a woman be like that?

498
02:27:03,580 --> 02:27:06,070
'"Why does every one do
What the others do?

499
02:27:07,000 --> 02:27:09,330
'"Can't a woman learn to use her head?

500
02:27:10,460 --> 02:27:13,080
'"Why do they do everything
Their mothers do?

501
02:27:13,300 --> 02:27:16,630
'"Why don't they grow up
Well, like their father instead?

502
02:27:16,840 --> 02:27:19,330
'"Why can't a woman take after a man?

503
02:27:19,970 --> 02:27:22,840
'"Men are so pleasant, so easy to please

504
02:27:23,350 --> 02:27:26,180
'"Whenever you're with them
You're always at ease

505
02:27:26,690 --> 02:27:29,690
'"Would you be slighted
lf I didn't speak for hours?

506
02:27:29,850 --> 02:27:32,480
'"Would you be livid
lf I had a drink or two?

507
02:27:33,190 --> 02:27:36,110
'"Would you be wounded
lf I never sent you flowers?

508
02:27:36,240 --> 02:27:38,990
'"Well, why can't a woman be like you?

509
02:27:40,410 --> 02:27:42,730
'"One man in a million may shout a bit

510
02:27:43,780 --> 02:27:46,450
'"Now and then
There's one with slight defects

511
02:27:47,160 --> 02:27:49,620
'"One perhaps whose truthfulness
You doubt a bit

512
02:27:49,710 --> 02:27:53,450
'"But by and large
We are a marvelous sex

513
02:27:53,750 --> 02:27:56,160
'"Why can't a woman take after a man?

514
02:27:56,880 --> 02:27:59,710
'"Cause men are so friendly
Good-natured and kind

515
02:28:00,170 --> 02:28:02,880
'"A better companion
You never will find

516
02:28:03,640 --> 02:28:06,510
'"lf I were hours late for dinner
Would you bellow?

517
02:28:06,810 --> 02:28:09,640
'"lf I forgot your silly birthday
Would you fuss?

518
02:28:10,020 --> 02:28:12,890
'"Would you complain
lf I took out another fellow?

519
02:28:13,270 --> 02:28:15,970
'"Well, why can't a woman be like us?'"

520
02:28:19,730 --> 02:28:21,690
Is Mr. Brewster Budgin there?

521
02:28:22,240 --> 02:28:26,070
Bruzzie, you'll never guess who this is.

522
02:28:27,870 --> 02:28:31,650
You're quite right, it is. Good heavens.
By George, what a memory.

523
02:28:32,750 --> 02:28:35,420
How are you, Bruzzie?
Nice to hear your voice.

524
02:28:36,460 --> 02:28:39,830
What? You don't say.
Has it really been 30 years, Bruzzie?

525
02:28:40,250 --> 02:28:41,500
Right. Yes, oceans of water.

526
02:28:41,590 --> 02:28:43,830
Listen, Bruzzie, I'll tell you why I rang up.

527
02:28:43,920 --> 02:28:47,670
Something rather unpleasant
has happened. Could I come and see you?

528
02:28:47,760 --> 02:28:49,800
I could, yes. Now, straight away?

529
02:28:49,890 --> 02:28:51,050
Right. Good. Thank you.

530
02:28:51,140 --> 02:28:53,550
Goodbye, Bruzzie. Thank you very much.

531
02:29:00,690 --> 02:29:03,520
Mrs. Pearce, I'm going along
to the Home Office.

532
02:29:04,230 --> 02:29:06,520
I do hope you find her, Colonel Pickering.

533
02:29:06,610 --> 02:29:08,400
Mr. Higgins will miss her.

534
02:29:08,610 --> 02:29:12,230
Mr. Higgins will miss her, eh?
Blast Mr. Higgins, I'll miss her!

535
02:29:24,170 --> 02:29:26,290
-Mrs. Pearce?
-Yes, sir.

536
02:29:26,670 --> 02:29:27,670
Where's the Colonel?

537
02:29:27,760 --> 02:29:29,910
He's gone to the Home Office, sir.

538
02:29:30,970 --> 02:29:35,920
There you are. I'm disturbed and he runs
for help. Now there's a good fellow.

539
02:29:37,770 --> 02:29:40,140
Mrs. Pearce, you're a woman.

540
02:29:41,480 --> 02:29:44,310
'"Why can't a woman be more like a man?

541
02:29:45,150 --> 02:29:47,980
'"Men are so decent
Such regular chaps

542
02:29:48,400 --> 02:29:51,020
'"Ready to help you
Through any mishaps

543
02:29:51,650 --> 02:29:54,230
'"Ready to buck you up
Whenever you are glum

544
02:29:54,820 --> 02:29:57,490
'"Why can't a woman be a chum?

545
02:29:58,740 --> 02:30:01,230
'"Why is thinking
Something women never do?

546
02:30:02,160 --> 02:30:04,620
'"And why is logic never even tried?

547
02:30:05,370 --> 02:30:08,210
'"Straightening up their hair
ls all they ever do

548
02:30:08,420 --> 02:30:11,870
'"Why don't they straighten up
The mess that's inside?

549
02:30:11,960 --> 02:30:14,540
'"Why can't a woman behave like a man?

550
02:30:15,260 --> 02:30:17,830
'"lf I was a woman
Who'd been to a ball

551
02:30:18,510 --> 02:30:21,180
'"Been hailed as a princess
By one and by all

552
02:30:21,850 --> 02:30:24,760
'"Would I start weeping
Like a bathtub overflowing?

553
02:30:24,930 --> 02:30:27,510
'"Or carry on as if my home were in a tree?

554
02:30:28,060 --> 02:30:31,060
'"Would I run off
And never tell me where I'm going?

555
02:30:31,310 --> 02:30:34,020
'"Why can't a woman be like me?'"

556
02:30:38,360 --> 02:30:41,450
You mean that after you'd done
this wonderful thing for them...

557
02:30:41,530 --> 02:30:43,030
...without making a mistake...

558
02:30:43,120 --> 02:30:45,110
...they just sat there
and never said a word?

559
02:30:45,200 --> 02:30:48,990
Never petted you, or admired you,
or told you how splendid you'd been?

560
02:30:49,080 --> 02:30:49,750
Not a word.

561
02:30:49,830 --> 02:30:53,030
They just congratulated each other
on how marvelous they'd been.

562
02:30:53,130 --> 02:30:55,620
The next moment, how glad they were
it was all over...

563
02:30:55,710 --> 02:30:57,500
...and what a bore it had all been.

564
02:30:57,590 --> 02:31:00,840
This is appalling. I should not
have thrown my slippers at him.

565
02:31:00,930 --> 02:31:03,170
I should have thrown the fire irons.

566
02:31:03,300 --> 02:31:04,470
Who's that?

567
02:31:04,600 --> 02:31:07,300
Henry. I knew it wouldn't be too long.

568
02:31:08,890 --> 02:31:10,270
Now, remember...

569
02:31:11,020 --> 02:31:15,350
...you not only danced with a prince
last night, you behaved like a princess.

570
02:31:22,240 --> 02:31:24,940
Mother, the most confounded thing....
Do you--

571
02:31:28,490 --> 02:31:29,410
You!

572
02:31:30,240 --> 02:31:33,360
Good afternoon, Professor Higgins.
Are you quite well?

573
02:31:34,830 --> 02:31:38,960
Of course you are. You are never ill.
Would you care for some tea?

574
02:31:39,750 --> 02:31:42,620
Don't you dare try that game on me.
I taught it to you.

575
02:31:42,710 --> 02:31:44,460
Get up, come home and stop being a fool.

576
02:31:44,550 --> 02:31:46,090
You've caused me enough trouble.

577
02:31:46,180 --> 02:31:50,170
Very nicely put indeed, Henry.
No woman could resist such an invitation.

578
02:31:50,260 --> 02:31:51,840
How did this baggage get here?

579
02:31:51,930 --> 02:31:54,880
Eliza came to see me this morning
and I was delighted to have her.

580
02:31:54,980 --> 02:31:57,930
If you don't promise to behave yourself
I'll ask you to leave.

581
02:31:58,020 --> 02:32:00,010
I'm to put on my Sunday manners
for this...

582
02:32:00,110 --> 02:32:03,890
...thing that I created out of the squashed
cabbage leaves of Covent Garden?

583
02:32:03,980 --> 02:32:05,730
That's precisely what I mean.

584
02:32:05,820 --> 02:32:07,400
I'll see her damned first.

585
02:32:07,490 --> 02:32:10,610
However did you learn good manners
with my son around?

586
02:32:10,820 --> 02:32:15,150
It was very difficult. I should never have
known how ladies and gentlemen behave...

587
02:32:15,240 --> 02:32:17,870
...if it hadn't been for Colonel Pickering.

588
02:32:19,290 --> 02:32:21,530
He showed me that he felt
and thought about me...

589
02:32:21,630 --> 02:32:24,990
...as if I were something better
than a common flower girl.

590
02:32:27,630 --> 02:32:31,210
You see, Mrs. Higgins,
apart from the things one can pick up...

591
02:32:31,380 --> 02:32:35,130
...the difference between a lady
and a flower girl isn't how she behaves...

592
02:32:35,220 --> 02:32:37,010
...but how she is treated.

593
02:32:39,810 --> 02:32:42,300
I'll always be a flower girl
to Professor Higgins...

594
02:32:42,390 --> 02:32:46,010
...because he always treats me
as a flower girl and always will.

595
02:32:46,730 --> 02:32:48,850
I'll always be a lady to Colonel Pickering...

596
02:32:48,940 --> 02:32:52,230
...because he always treats me
as a lady and always will.

597
02:32:57,120 --> 02:32:58,580
Henry, don't grind your teeth.

598
02:32:58,660 --> 02:33:01,490
The bishop is here.
Shall I show him into the garden?

599
02:33:01,580 --> 02:33:04,070
The bishop and the professor?
Good heavens, no!

600
02:33:04,160 --> 02:33:05,990
I should be excommunicated.

601
02:33:06,290 --> 02:33:08,200
I'll see him in the library.

602
02:33:08,960 --> 02:33:11,630
Eliza, if my son starts breaking up things...

603
02:33:11,840 --> 02:33:14,540
...l give you full permission
to have him evicted.

604
02:33:14,630 --> 02:33:18,840
Henry, I suggest you stick to two subjects:
the weather and your health.

605
02:33:46,660 --> 02:33:48,700
You've had a bit of your own back,
as you say.

606
02:33:48,790 --> 02:33:52,210
Have you had enough and will you
be reasonable or do you want any more?

607
02:33:52,290 --> 02:33:54,290
You want me back to pick up
your slippers...

608
02:33:54,380 --> 02:33:57,410
...and put up with your tempers
and fetch and carry for you.

609
02:33:57,510 --> 02:33:59,300
I didn't say I wanted you back at all.

610
02:33:59,380 --> 02:34:00,760
Then what are we talking about?

611
02:34:00,840 --> 02:34:02,470
Well, about you, not about me.

612
02:34:02,550 --> 02:34:05,260
If you come back you'll be treated
as you always have.

613
02:34:05,350 --> 02:34:07,590
I can't change my nature or my manners.

614
02:34:07,680 --> 02:34:10,520
My manners are exactly
the same as Colonel Pickering's.

615
02:34:10,600 --> 02:34:14,380
That's not true. He treats a flower girl
as if she were a duchess.

616
02:34:14,520 --> 02:34:16,760
I treat a duchess
as if she was a flower girl.

617
02:34:16,860 --> 02:34:19,020
I see. The same to everybody.

618
02:34:19,480 --> 02:34:22,240
The great secret is not a question
of good manners...

619
02:34:22,320 --> 02:34:25,770
...or bad manners
or any particular sort of manner...

620
02:34:26,280 --> 02:34:29,650
...but having the same manner
for all human souls.

621
02:34:31,540 --> 02:34:33,940
The question is not
whether I treat you rudely...

622
02:34:34,040 --> 02:34:37,460
...but whether you've ever heard me
treat anyone else better.

623
02:34:37,540 --> 02:34:39,500
I don't care how you treat me.

624
02:34:39,590 --> 02:34:42,670
I don't mind your swearing at me.
I shouldn't mind a black eye.

625
02:34:42,760 --> 02:34:45,840
I've had one before this.
But I won't be passed over!

626
02:34:46,050 --> 02:34:47,920
Get out of my way,
for I won't stop for you.

627
02:34:48,010 --> 02:34:50,130
You talk about me as though
I was a motorbus.

628
02:34:50,220 --> 02:34:54,430
So you are a motorbus. All bounce and go
and no consideration for anybody.

629
02:34:54,680 --> 02:34:57,440
But I can get along without you.
Don't you think I can't!

630
02:34:57,520 --> 02:34:59,930
I know you can. I told you, you could.

631
02:35:03,360 --> 02:35:05,930
You've never wondered, I suppose,
whether...

632
02:35:06,030 --> 02:35:08,570
...whether I could get along without you?

633
02:35:09,660 --> 02:35:12,690
Don't you try to get around me.
You'll have to.

634
02:35:13,910 --> 02:35:16,530
So I can, without you or any soul on earth.

635
02:35:19,670 --> 02:35:23,880
I shall miss you, Eliza. I've learned
something from your idiotic notions.

636
02:35:24,540 --> 02:35:27,080
I confess that humbly and gratefully.

637
02:35:30,050 --> 02:35:32,420
Well, you have my voice
on your gramophone.

638
02:35:32,510 --> 02:35:37,010
When you feel lonely without me you can
turn it on. It has no feelings to hurt.

639
02:35:38,520 --> 02:35:41,270
Well, I can't turn your soul on.

640
02:35:43,940 --> 02:35:46,180
You are a devil!

641
02:35:47,150 --> 02:35:49,640
You can twist the heart in a girl
just as easily...

642
02:35:49,730 --> 02:35:52,190
...as some can twist her arms to hurt her.

643
02:35:52,280 --> 02:35:54,110
What am I to come back for?

644
02:35:54,450 --> 02:35:56,520
For the fun of it. That's why I took you on.

645
02:35:56,620 --> 02:35:59,370
You may throw me out tomorrow
if I don't do everything you want.

646
02:35:59,450 --> 02:36:02,870
Yes. And you may walk out tomorrow
if I don't do everything you want.

647
02:36:02,960 --> 02:36:04,150
And live with my father?

648
02:36:04,250 --> 02:36:06,790
Yes, or sell flowers.
Would you rather marry Pickering?

649
02:36:06,880 --> 02:36:10,620
I wouldn't marry you if you asked me
and you're nearer my age then what he is.

650
02:36:10,710 --> 02:36:13,920
-Than he is.
-I'll talk as I like, you're not my teacher.

651
02:36:14,010 --> 02:36:16,840
That's not what I want
and don't you think it is.

652
02:36:16,930 --> 02:36:19,170
I've always had chaps enough
wanting me that way.

653
02:36:19,260 --> 02:36:22,350
Freddy Hill writes me twice
and three times a day. Sheets and sheets.

654
02:36:22,430 --> 02:36:26,380
In short, you want me to be
as infatuated about you as he is, is that it?

655
02:36:26,480 --> 02:36:30,470
No, I don't. That's not the sort of feeling
I want from you.

656
02:36:31,570 --> 02:36:33,310
I want a little kindness.

657
02:36:33,730 --> 02:36:37,430
I know I'm a common, ignorant girl,
and you're a book-learned gentleman...

658
02:36:37,530 --> 02:36:39,770
...but I'm not dirt under your feet.

659
02:36:40,030 --> 02:36:45,030
What I done...what I did was not
for the taxis and the dresses...

660
02:36:45,450 --> 02:36:49,120
...but because we were pleasant together
and I come to...came...

661
02:36:50,460 --> 02:36:51,950
...to care for you.

662
02:36:52,250 --> 02:36:54,040
Not to want you to make love to me...

663
02:36:54,130 --> 02:36:57,210
...and not forgetting the difference
between us, but...

664
02:36:57,300 --> 02:36:58,960
...more friendly like.

665
02:37:01,180 --> 02:37:03,420
Well, of course. That's how I feel.

666
02:37:04,050 --> 02:37:07,640
And how Pickering feels.
Eliza, you're a fool!

667
02:37:07,720 --> 02:37:09,100
That's not the proper answer.

668
02:37:09,180 --> 02:37:11,140
It's the only answer
till you stop being an idiot.

669
02:37:11,230 --> 02:37:13,390
To be a lady, you must stop
feeling neglected...

670
02:37:13,480 --> 02:37:16,100
...if men don't spend half their time
sniveling over you...

671
02:37:16,190 --> 02:37:18,230
...and the other half giving you black eyes.

672
02:37:18,320 --> 02:37:20,720
You find me cold, unfeeling, selfish,
don't you?

673
02:37:20,820 --> 02:37:22,900
Off with you to the sort of people you like.

674
02:37:22,990 --> 02:37:24,900
Marry a sentimental hog
with lots of money...

675
02:37:24,990 --> 02:37:27,740
...and thick lips to kiss you,
and thick boots to kick you.

676
02:37:27,830 --> 02:37:30,990
If you can't appreciate what you have,
then get what you can appreciate.

677
02:37:31,330 --> 02:37:34,160
I can't talk to you.
You always turn everything against me.

678
02:37:34,250 --> 02:37:35,960
I'm always in the wrong.

679
02:37:36,170 --> 02:37:38,410
Don't be too sure you have me
under your feet...

680
02:37:38,500 --> 02:37:40,630
...to be trampled on and talked down.

681
02:37:40,710 --> 02:37:44,250
I'll marry Freddy, I will,
as soon as I'm able to support him.

682
02:37:45,720 --> 02:37:48,340
The poor devil who couldn't get a job
as an errand boy...

683
02:37:48,430 --> 02:37:50,390
...even if he had the guts to try?

684
02:37:50,470 --> 02:37:54,220
Don't you understand?
I have made you a consort for a king!

685
02:37:54,390 --> 02:37:57,350
Freddy loves me.
That makes him king enough for me.

686
02:37:57,440 --> 02:38:00,440
I don't want him to work.
He wasn't brought up to do it as I was.

687
02:38:00,520 --> 02:38:02,270
I'll go and be a teacher.

688
02:38:02,690 --> 02:38:04,680
What'll you teach, in heaven's name?

689
02:38:04,780 --> 02:38:07,310
What you taught me. I'll teach phonetics.

690
02:38:11,700 --> 02:38:15,950
I'll offer myself as an assistant
to that brilliant Hungarian.

691
02:38:16,830 --> 02:38:20,490
What, that imposter? That humbug?
That toadying ignoramus?

692
02:38:20,870 --> 02:38:23,030
Teach him my methods, my discoveries?

693
02:38:23,130 --> 02:38:25,750
You take one step in that direction,
I'll wring your neck!

694
02:38:25,840 --> 02:38:29,290
Wring away! What do I care?
I knew you'd strike me one day.

695
02:38:32,550 --> 02:38:35,510
That's done you, 'Enry 'lggins, it 'as.

696
02:38:35,600 --> 02:38:38,680
Now, I don't care for your bullyin'
an' your big talk.

697
02:38:39,980 --> 02:38:41,850
'"What a fool I was

698
02:38:41,940 --> 02:38:43,560
'"What a dominated fool

699
02:38:43,850 --> 02:38:46,640
'"To think you were the earth and sky

700
02:38:47,230 --> 02:38:48,940
'"What a fool I was

701
02:38:49,030 --> 02:38:50,730
'"What an addle-pated fool

702
02:38:50,900 --> 02:38:54,320
'"What a mutton-headed dolt was I

703
02:38:55,490 --> 02:38:58,740
'"No, my reverberating friend

704
02:38:59,200 --> 02:39:03,330
'"You are not the beginning and the end'"

705
02:39:06,080 --> 02:39:07,580
You impudent hussy!

706
02:39:07,790 --> 02:39:12,340
There's not an idea in your head or a word
in your mouth that I haven't put there.

707
02:39:13,840 --> 02:39:18,420
'"There'll be spring every year without you

708
02:39:19,260 --> 02:39:22,470
'"England still will be here without you

709
02:39:23,180 --> 02:39:26,880
'"There'll be fruit on the tree
And a shore by the sea

710
02:39:26,980 --> 02:39:30,180
'"There'll be crumpets and tea without you

711
02:39:30,770 --> 02:39:33,940
'"Art and music will thrive without you

712
02:39:34,610 --> 02:39:37,780
'"Somehow Keats will survive without you

713
02:39:38,450 --> 02:39:42,230
'"And there still will be rain
On that plain down in Spain

714
02:39:42,330 --> 02:39:45,530
'"Even that will remain without you

715
02:39:46,120 --> 02:39:47,860
'"l can do...

716
02:39:49,790 --> 02:39:51,250
'"...without you

717
02:39:52,460 --> 02:39:55,210
'"You, dear friend

718
02:39:55,300 --> 02:39:58,500
'"Who talk so well

719
02:39:59,800 --> 02:40:03,300
'"You can go to

720
02:40:03,510 --> 02:40:06,180
'"Hartford, Hereford and Hampshire

721
02:40:06,850 --> 02:40:09,800
'"They can still rule the land without you

722
02:40:10,480 --> 02:40:13,730
'"Windsor Castle will stand without you

723
02:40:14,270 --> 02:40:17,890
'"And without much ado
We can all muddle through

724
02:40:17,980 --> 02:40:19,770
'"Without you! '"

725
02:40:19,990 --> 02:40:21,730
You brazen hussy!

726
02:40:22,450 --> 02:40:26,150
'"Without your pulling it the tide comes in

727
02:40:26,740 --> 02:40:30,660
'"Without your twirling it the earth can spin

728
02:40:30,830 --> 02:40:35,320
'"Without your pushing them
the clouds roll by

729
02:40:36,130 --> 02:40:41,250
'"lf they can do without you, Ducky,
So can I

730
02:40:41,510 --> 02:40:45,000
'"l shall not feel alone without you

731
02:40:45,260 --> 02:40:48,460
'"l can stand on my own without you

732
02:40:49,010 --> 02:40:52,800
'"So go back in your shell
I can do bloody well--'"

733
02:40:53,350 --> 02:40:57,130
'"By George, I really did it
I did it, I did it

734
02:40:57,310 --> 02:40:59,980
'"l said I'd make a woman and indeed I did

735
02:41:00,150 --> 02:41:02,850
'"l knew that I could do it
I knew it, I knew it

736
02:41:03,030 --> 02:41:05,560
'"l said I'd make a woman
and succeed I did'"

737
02:41:05,940 --> 02:41:07,740
Eliza, you're magnificent.

738
02:41:08,110 --> 02:41:10,600
Five minutes ago you were
a millstone around my neck...

739
02:41:10,700 --> 02:41:12,740
...and now you're a tower of strength.

740
02:41:12,830 --> 02:41:14,450
A consort battleship.

741
02:41:15,830 --> 02:41:17,410
I like you this way.

742
02:41:19,670 --> 02:41:23,500
Goodbye, Professor Higgins.
You shall not be seeing me again.

743
02:41:37,140 --> 02:41:38,170
Mother!

744
02:41:41,480 --> 02:41:43,720
What is it, Henry? What's happened?

745
02:41:45,520 --> 02:41:46,690
She's gone.

746
02:41:46,820 --> 02:41:49,390
Well, of course, dear.
What did you expect?

747
02:41:52,860 --> 02:41:54,060
What am I to do?

748
02:41:54,160 --> 02:41:55,780
Do without, I suppose.

749
02:41:57,530 --> 02:41:59,280
And so I shall.

750
02:42:02,540 --> 02:42:05,540
If the Higgins' oxygen burns up
her little lungs...

751
02:42:05,670 --> 02:42:08,420
...let her seek some stuffiness
that suits her.

752
02:42:09,210 --> 02:42:12,710
She's an owl sickened
by a few days of my sunshine.

753
02:42:13,090 --> 02:42:15,080
Let her go. I can do without her.

754
02:42:15,180 --> 02:42:17,630
I can do without anyone.
I have my own soul!

755
02:42:17,720 --> 02:42:20,550
My own spark of divine fire!

756
02:42:24,770 --> 02:42:26,100
Bravo, Eliza.

757
02:42:46,540 --> 02:42:49,700
'"Damn, damn, damn, damn

758
02:42:52,040 --> 02:42:54,200
'"l've grown accustomed to her face

759
02:42:58,010 --> 02:43:00,050
'"She almost makes the day begin

760
02:43:01,180 --> 02:43:04,510
'"l've grown accustomed to the tune
That she whistles night and noon

761
02:43:04,600 --> 02:43:08,340
'"Her smiles, her frowns
Her ups, her downs

762
02:43:08,470 --> 02:43:10,380
'"Are second nature to me now

763
02:43:11,640 --> 02:43:13,890
'"Like breathing out and breathing in

764
02:43:15,020 --> 02:43:18,390
'"l was serenely independent and content
Before we met

765
02:43:18,980 --> 02:43:21,940
'"Surely I could always be that way again

766
02:43:24,110 --> 02:43:27,810
'"And yet I've grown
Accustomed to her looks

767
02:43:28,790 --> 02:43:30,490
'"Accustomed to her voice

768
02:43:31,120 --> 02:43:34,870
'"Accustomed to her face'"

769
02:43:49,680 --> 02:43:50,920
Marry Freddy.

770
02:43:51,600 --> 02:43:55,680
What an infantile idea. What a heartless,
wicked, brainless thing to do.

771
02:43:56,440 --> 02:43:59,140
But she'll regret it. She'll regret it.

772
02:43:59,650 --> 02:44:02,320
It's doomed before they even take the vow!

773
02:44:03,980 --> 02:44:07,650
'"l can see her now
Mrs. Freddy Eynsford-Hill

774
02:44:07,820 --> 02:44:10,310
'"ln a wretched little flat above a store

775
02:44:10,950 --> 02:44:13,820
'"l can see her now, not a penny in the till

776
02:44:13,910 --> 02:44:16,450
'"And a bill collector beating at the door

777
02:44:17,000 --> 02:44:19,670
'"She'll try to teach the things I taught her

778
02:44:19,920 --> 02:44:22,120
'"And end up selling flowers instead

779
02:44:22,960 --> 02:44:25,040
'"Begging for her bread and water

780
02:44:25,460 --> 02:44:28,170
'"While her husband has
his breakfast in bed

781
02:44:31,760 --> 02:44:36,220
'"ln a year or so
when she's prematurely gray

782
02:44:36,310 --> 02:44:39,180
'"And the blossom in her cheek
has turned to chalk

783
02:44:39,980 --> 02:44:43,180
'"She'll come home and lo
he'll have upped and run away

784
02:44:43,310 --> 02:44:46,180
'"With a social-climbing heiress
from New York

785
02:44:46,440 --> 02:44:47,720
'"Poor Eliza

786
02:44:47,820 --> 02:44:49,440
'"How simply frightful

787
02:44:49,530 --> 02:44:51,150
'"How humiliating

788
02:44:51,860 --> 02:44:53,360
'"How delightful

789
02:44:56,200 --> 02:44:59,070
'"How poignant it will be
On that inevitable night

790
02:44:59,240 --> 02:45:01,950
'"When she hammers on my door
ln tears and rags

791
02:45:02,460 --> 02:45:05,540
'"Miserable and lonely
Repentant and contrite

792
02:45:06,380 --> 02:45:08,870
'"Will I take her in
Or hurl her to the wolves?

793
02:45:08,960 --> 02:45:11,830
'"Give her kindness
Or the treatment she deserves?

794
02:45:12,210 --> 02:45:15,420
'"Will I take her back
Or throw the baggage out?

795
02:45:18,390 --> 02:45:20,430
'"Well, I'm a most forgiving man

796
02:45:21,220 --> 02:45:23,760
'"The sort who never could, ever would

797
02:45:24,230 --> 02:45:27,350
'"Take a position
and staunchly never budge

798
02:45:30,980 --> 02:45:32,690
'"A most forgiving man

799
02:45:35,940 --> 02:45:37,980
'"But I shall never take her back

800
02:45:39,110 --> 02:45:41,270
'"lf she were crawling on her knees

801
02:45:41,870 --> 02:45:44,490
'"Let her promise to atone
Let her shiver, let her moan

802
02:45:44,580 --> 02:45:48,240
'"l'll slam the door
And let the hellcat freeze'"

803
02:45:51,380 --> 02:45:53,000
Marry Freddy.

804
02:46:07,890 --> 02:46:10,100
'"But I'm so used to hear her say

805
02:46:10,980 --> 02:46:12,720
'"'Good morning' every day

806
02:46:13,520 --> 02:46:15,480
'"Her joys, her woes

807
02:46:16,150 --> 02:46:18,720
'"Her highs, her lows

808
02:46:18,940 --> 02:46:20,940
'"Are second nature to me now

809
02:46:22,900 --> 02:46:25,150
'"Like breathing out and breathing in

810
02:46:26,990 --> 02:46:30,570
'"l'm very grateful she's a woman
And so easy to forget

811
02:46:31,580 --> 02:46:34,910
'"Rather like a habit one can always break

812
02:46:37,670 --> 02:46:41,670
'"And yet I've grown
Accustomed to the trace

813
02:46:42,670 --> 02:46:45,210
'"Of something in the air

814
02:46:46,680 --> 02:46:51,220
'"Accustomed to her face'"

815
02:48:28,860 --> 02:48:33,850
Oh, we are proud. He ain't above
givin' lessons, not 'im. I 'eard 'im say so.

816
02:48:34,530 --> 02:48:36,650
I ain't come here to ask
for any compliment...

817
02:48:36,740 --> 02:48:39,770
...and if my money's not good enough,
I can go elsewhere.

818
02:48:39,870 --> 02:48:41,150
Good enough for what?

819
02:48:41,240 --> 02:48:43,860
Good enough for you.
Now you know, don't ya?

820
02:48:44,040 --> 02:48:46,440
I'm come to 'ave lessons.
And to pay for 'em, too...

821
02:48:46,540 --> 02:48:47,570
...make no mistake.

822
02:48:47,660 --> 02:48:49,410
What do you want, my girl?

823
02:48:49,500 --> 02:48:52,870
I want to be a lady in a flow'r shop,
'stead o' sellin'...

824
02:48:53,000 --> 02:48:55,410
...at the corner of Tottenham Court Road.

825
02:48:55,500 --> 02:49:00,000
But they won't take me unless I can talk
more genteel. He said he could teach me.

826
02:49:00,720 --> 02:49:05,710
Well, 'ere I am ready to pay. Not askin'
any favor, and he treats me as if I was dirt.

827
02:49:06,510 --> 02:49:10,260
I know what lessons cost as well as you do
and I'm ready to pay.

828
02:49:10,890 --> 02:49:14,060
I won't give more than a shillin'.
Take it or leave it.

829
02:49:14,400 --> 02:49:18,390
It's almost irresistible.
She's so deliciously low.

830
02:49:19,190 --> 02:49:21,770
So horribly dirty. I'll take it.

831
02:49:22,490 --> 02:49:25,650
I'll make a duchess
of this draggle-tailed guttersnipe.

832
02:49:27,490 --> 02:49:30,330
I washed my face and 'ands
before I come, I did.

833
02:49:44,930 --> 02:49:47,000
Where the devil are my slippers?
